<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAFAYETTE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 What's a hot tub doing at the Farm Science Review? `` The farmer likes hot tubs just as much as anyone does. We have a tendency to think the farmer is not a normal person. But of course he is,'' said <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Fendrick </PERSON>, manager of the farm equipment exposition at the <ORGANIZATION> Molly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caren </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, 20 miles west of <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>. Organizers of the three-day event say the 600-plus demonstrations and displays have changed over the years. `` We sat back and thought, ` How come we can attract the farmer but not his wife, his family, his neighbors?''' <PERSON> Fendrick </PERSON> said Wednesday. So along with tractor demonstrations and free samples of pesticide, the review offered tips on how to remove chocolate stains from linen, manage personal finances, update a wardrobe with inexpensive accessories and eat at Pizza Hut without gaining much weight. Information also was available on owning a bed-and-breakfast inn and breeding a pet llama. Ten or 15 years ago, the typical visitor at the review was white, male, between 50 and 60 years old, wore overalls and attended the event by himself. `` Today he's wearing designer jeans, his wife is with him, and she's usually pushing the stroller,'' <PERSON> Fendrick </PERSON> said. `` A lot of them out there are in their 30s.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Glasnost notwithstanding, there are still some unknown details about Soviet leaders. Such as, how big is Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>'s head? <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> officials wanted to know that before <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>'s scheduled arrival in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hole </LOCATION> today for two days of talks with Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> Officials from the <ORGANIZATION> Cowboy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> did n't want to cause an international embarrassment by presenting the minister with an ill-fitting <PERSON> Stetson </PERSON>. `` We tried calling the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Embassy </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. They said it's just kind of average. We did n't really know what that meant,'' said <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>, spokesman for Gov. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>. So they rang up the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, counting on the resourcefulness of the American intelligence network. It took two days of research to find an answer: 60 centimeters. `` We were n't quite sure what that meant,'' <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> said, adding that officials think it corresponds to a size 7 -LCB-. The cowboy hat is intended to help <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> fit in at a western barbecue to be thrown by <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> on Saturday night at the end of the two-day talks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members returned from summer break to temporary quarters in a former print shop and went to work on folding chairs and cafeteria-style tables instead of their usual stately chairs and desks. The House is being housed in an office building so its Capitol chamber can be restored during the next few months. Low ceilings made the noise level louder than usual Wednesday, and legislators practically had to step over each other in crowded aisles. One lawmaker said he could n't find a bathroom. `` This would n't pass the inspection for a dairy barn,'' Rep. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Gnodtke </PERSON> said, `` but I guess it's good enough for legislators.'' Despite the tight space and the noise, most lawmakers gave good reviews to their temporary chamber. `` I was all set to come here and gripe, but I want to make sure the right people get complimented,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>. House Speaker <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodak </PERSON> said he hoped members would start using their phones to call each other on the floor to cut down on traffic and noise.
</TEXT>
