<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia-War     09-21 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia-War,0752</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodians Fear More War After Vietnamese Withdrawal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report. Vietnamese pullout set to be completed
by Sept. 26.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At 6 a.m. one recent Thursday, Soun Sundary, gentle and serene at 21, gave birth to her first child and held her up to a <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> that has known only war for two decades. `` I do n't know about the future, whether there will be peace or not,'' she said as the sun shone into her hospital room after days of monsoon rains. She and her husband, <PERSON> Soun </PERSON> <PERSON> Rithy </PERSON>, 25, have spent most of their lives with their tragic nation in turmoil and mass deaths _ the civil war of 1970-75, the fanatical communist <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> rule of 1975-78 and the fighting since <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> invaded in late 1978. Seven members of their two families died in the murderous scourge of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> who defeated a pro-West government in 1975. The couple and their daughter are likely to see more killing in the years ahead, even though the Vietnamese are pulling out. Rithy had come to <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> for the birth of his child but is returning to southern <LOCATION> Koh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> province, where he has fought as a government soldier for seven years against the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> and other guerrillas. Peace talks in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> have collapsed. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s pullout, due to be completed Sept. 26, will leave the Vietnamese-installed <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> government in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> facing the guerrillas alone in what could be the war's most chaotic and violent phase. `` We would like to have peace, really,'' Vice Premier <PERSON> Kong </PERSON> <PERSON> Sam-Ol </PERSON> said in n interview. `` For almost 20 years, our people have known more about killing and war than peace.'' Most feared is the possibility that <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s pullout will allow the return of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, the black pajama-clad fighters who killed hundreds of thousands of people in torture chambers and slave labor camps after they took over in 1975. The government claims the army will have no problems handling the guerrillas. Many others do not feel as confident. Some <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> residents have been stocking rice in case supplies are cut off by escalating fighting, said <PERSON> Khieu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanharith </PERSON>, editor of the government-sponsored weekly Kampuchea. Some senior government officials have told Western aid workers they are saving money in case they have to flee. `` They do n't know what is going to happen after September if there are problems with the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>,'' one aid worker said. `` They believe if there are problems, the first problems would be for them.'' At <LOCATION> Kompong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chhnang </LOCATION>, just north of <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION>, Maj. <PERSON> Chhour </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandoeun </PERSON>, the provincial military commander, said his nine battalions are hard pressed in their fight against the 300 <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas in the area. `` They do n't stay in one place and we do n't know all their hiding places,'' he said. An aid official said the government's military draft appears to be widening. A few months ago, some parents forbade their sons to leave the house as overzealous recruiters yanked men off the streets. Some youths flee to the border with <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, only to be rounded up by the guerrillas for service. A 10 p.m.-5 a.m. curfew was lifted in April, but the climate of war still pervades this riverside capital. In July, authorities closed dance halls that had been packed nightly since they were permitted to open last year. Mayor <PERSON> Thong </PERSON> <PERSON> Khong </PERSON> blamed drunken quarrels and said only the rich could visit them anyway. `` At that time, there was increased fighting at the border and it was difficult to justify the sacrifice at the border and the good life in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION>,'' one foreign-aid official said. For many years, popular support for the Vietnamese-backed government had stemmed mostly from its being the only alternative to the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>. With <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s pullout, <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> extended economic reforms to include a freeing up of private trade in an effort to raise primitive living conditions. Ironically, it created a new security problem by worsening corruption among officials, and corruption was a factor that helped the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> topple <PERSON> Lon </PERSON> <PERSON> Nol </PERSON>'s pro-West government in 1975. The reforms reduced somewhat the gulf between the people and their leaders But in addition to the fear of more war remains the widespread fear of the authorities and `` the police,'' who are thought to be everywhere.
</TEXT>
