<HEAD>12-Year-Old Raises $587 for Bullet-Proof Vests for Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRISTOL, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police thanked a 12-year-old boy for raising $ 587 to buy them two bulletproof vests. Seventh-grader <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Flores </PERSON> said he learned of the dangers facing police officers when he read a magazine article describing how a bulletproof vest saved an officer's life. He visited the police department, where he learned that the department had only enough of the $ 300 vests for about a third of its officers. So, he placed jars for contributions in stores, raising about $ 300. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, whose father is a doctor, then got more than $ 200 from doctors at <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> voted Monday to let the police department buy two vests with the $ 587 he raised. `` He did it on his own,'' Lt. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Killiany </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` We're very appreciative of the efforts of this youth.'' It was n't <PERSON> Flores </PERSON>' first contribution to the city. He has volunteered to help senior citizens and with clients of the <ORGANIZATION> Bristol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Retarded _ and now he's looking for more volunteer work. `` I'll find something,'' he said.
