<HEAD>Death Toll From Typhoon Rises to 162</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The death toll from a powerful typhoon that hit <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s east coast over the weekend has risen to 162, with 354 people still missing, an official newspaper reported today. The <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> Daily, quoting flood control officials in <LOCATION> Zhejiang </LOCATION> province, said 692 people were injured and property losses from Typhoon Vera were estimated at $ 350 million. The typhoon, the most powerful to hit the province in 27 years, flooded 857,000 acres of farmland and washed out 40,000 acres of crops. Earlier television newscasts showed toppled buildings, flattened fields and workers rebuilding the shoreline with stones and sandbags. <LOCATION> Zhejiang </LOCATION>, located just south of <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, was also hit by torrential storms this July that killed 122 people and caused economic losses of $ 405 million. `` These natural calamities have brought appalling losses to the province's people and property as well as to its industrial and agricultural base,'' the flood control headquarters said. Last year, summer storms in the disaster-prone province killed an estimated 400.
