<SECOND>PM-Teddy Bear,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>World's Most Expensive Teddy Bear Bought As Anniversary Gift</HEAD>
<HEAD>By JESSICA BALDWIN</HEAD>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s was surprised when a well-preserved, 67-year-old teddy bear sold for a record $ 86,000. So was the buyer. `` His first words were, ` You're kidding','' <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, who was an intermediary in the deal, said Wednesday. However, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said, his <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> friend was prepared to pay even more and was delighted to bag the bear as a 42nd anniversary present for his wife. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> refused to identify the buyer. The actual bidding was done by stockbroker <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, 26, of <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION>, who was given a blank check and sent to <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on Tuesday. `` I could tell from his voice he was ashen,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said, `` and he said ... the auction's just over and I've got the bear.' `` And I said ` well done, <PERSON> James </PERSON>' and then he said ` you'd better sit down because I paid 50,000 -LRB- pounds -RRB-.' `` And I said ` You've done what?!''' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said he waited a few hours before phoning his American friend. `` I guess he might have figured on a third'' of that record price, said <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, who is chairman of the House of Nisbet teddy bear manufacturers in <LOCATION> Weston-super-Mare </LOCATION> in southwest <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. `` He's is very pleased. He was determined to have it.'' The buyer and his wife are avid teddy-bear collectors, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said, and both happen to be as old as the record-breaking bear. The price is nearly five times the previous highest price for a teddy bear and 61 times its catalogue estimate, said <PERSON> Bunny </PERSON> <PERSON> Campione </PERSON>, a valuer for <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said his firm would like to do a replica of the bear. `` It's up to my friend, although it seems like we have the inside track,'' he said. The previous highest auction price for a teddy bear was $ 19,000 paid at a Christie's auction in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on May 18 for a Steiff bear made between 1906 and 1909 for Princess <LOCATION> Xenia </LOCATION>, a cousin of Czar <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>. Several bidders stayed in the race until the price reached $ 38,000, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. `` The other bidder after 24,000 pounds -LRB- $ 38,000 -RRB- was a telephone bidder and the general impression was that the caller was from <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. `` Bears are an art form like paintings,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. `` People are used to hearing about crazy figures like $ 400 million for paintings and this is the same kind of price inflation. It is a very rare bear.'' The German-made teddy, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> is thought to date from 1927. The bear is 24 inches long, has dual-plush fur in blond and brown, amber and black glass eyes measuring about 1 inch in diameter, swivel joints, a humped back and widely spaced pricked ears. It is believed that it was part of a batch of a few thousand, but Mrs. <PERSON> Campione </PERSON> said the bear was in unusually good condition. Before going to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the bear will on display at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teddy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Stratford-upon-Avon </LOCATION> this weekend.
