<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is supporting efforts to retain catastrophic medical insurance for retirees amid growing indications that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> may bow to pressure to repeal the program. `` Catastrophic meets a very real need in protecting senior citizens against financial ruin'' as a result of an illness, Secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Although some adjustments may be needed, he added, `` repeal would be a big mistake.'' But leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> acknowledged Wednesday the number of lawmakers who will vote to repeal the program outright is growing. Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, an author of the program and chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> probably will vote for repeal. Democratic leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> agreed to allow a repeal vote next week when the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> considers a <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> plan for keeping catastrophic care but scaling the program back. The program, the largest expansion ever of Medicare, is under attack from two groups of retirees: those who already are covered by a catastrophic plan, including federal retirees; and higher-income older Americans who object to paying for coverage for those at the bottom of the economic ladder. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said that although the administration prefers no changes in the program, it would support a modification backed by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> leaders of both parties. That proposal would eliminate coverage for most prescription drugs; scale back coverage of physicians' fees, and reduce the surtax on higher-income retirees that pays for most of the program. `` We want to do everything we can to preserve the core benefits'' in the program, <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> told the committee. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>, R-Mo., said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should repeal the program and consider a replacement as part of an overall national health strategy Sen. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, said any discussion of repeal should include recognition that `` people's lives are at stake.'' Repeal, he said, would amount to `` denying somebody the right to get an operation in a hospital and allow them to live ... without going bankrupt.''
