<SECOND>PM-Crop Insurance,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Crop Insurance Most Equitable Way to Aid Farmers, Report
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal crop insurance program needs improvements, but it is a better way to provide disaster aid to farmers than emergency loans and direct payments, a congressional report says. And a government commission says some changes could be made immediately in the crop insurance program to boost farmer participation beyond the current 25 percent. The program needs to be simplified and made more responsive, and the administration could be improved, <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Classen </PERSON>, co-chairmen of the Commission for the Improvement of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION>, told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on Wednesday. A <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> report said the federal government spent $ 17.6 billion between 1980 and 1988 assisting farmers who lost crops because of drought or other natural causes. About $ 6.9 billion of that was direct assistance, $ 6.4 billion came through emergency loan programs and $ 4.3 billion was spent to subsidize crop insurance. However, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said the crop insurance program is a more equitable and efficient way to provide aid to farmers. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said its investigation showed that most farmers do n't buy crop insurance because they are used to having <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> come to the rescue with special assistance whenever there is a major crisis. For example, $ 4 billion in direct payments were made in 1988 by emergency act of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> because of the severe drought, said the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>. Rep. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> English, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., who chairs the subcommittee on conservation, credit and rural development, said 65 percent to 70 percent participation in the crop insurance program is needed to make it work `` We can not continue to do this,'' English said, referring to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' ad hoc approach to agricultural disasters. `` The costs are too high.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Harman </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, said that in examining disaster assistance programs, his agency found that direct payments or emergency loans can result in different treatment for similarly affected disaster victims. `` In contrast, the terms of compensation under crop insurance are determined before a disaster occurs and therefore, crop insurance provides farmers equitable assistance more consistently,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> also found that crop insurance, because it is consistently available, allows farmers more flexibility in long-range planning. `` We recognize that the crop insurance program has had a history of management problems that, in the short term, makes it difficult to justify the current crop insurance program as the sole source of disaster assistance to farmers,'' said <PERSON> Harman </PERSON>. He said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should provide a transition period if it decides to rely exclusively on crop insurance for disaster assistance. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Classen </PERSON> testified before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on conservation, credit and rural development. `` The commission believes that many changes to effect immediate administrative improvements in the program can be made under existing law by the secretary of agriculture and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Classen </PERSON>. `` These changes would foster increased participation by farmers.''
