<HEAD>Gorbachev Shows Renewed Strength in Politburo Shake-up'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s swift elimination of a quarter of the ruling Politburo, including two leading conservatives, demonstrates his political strength just as doubts about his staying power were gaining currency in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The dramatic power play, executed on the eve of Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>'s meeting with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at the White House, served to counter suggestions that the Soviet president had been weakened by increasing public frustration with worsening economic conditions and heightened ethnic tensions. The shake-up could be seen as strengthening <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>'s hand as he seeks to revitalize the arms control process during talks with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. With successive moves during the last year to consolidate his power, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> may now have broken high-level resistance and opened the way for sweeping changes that reformers say are needed if <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s program of economic restructuring is to shake the country out of the doldrums. The party's <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meeting that shuffled the makeup of the party's Politburo also handed <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> an early opportunity next year to use a party congress to reach further down into the party apparatus to shake out bureaucrats blamed for smothering reform. The president and <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief successfully instituted glasnost, which has brought more open criticism and debate. He overhauled the political system to encourage competitive elections and representative oversight of government operations. And his `` new thinking'' in foreign policy has done much to dispel what he called his country's `` enemy image'' abroad. But <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms so far have failed to relieve the grinding economic hardship that has left consumers frustrated by barren cupboards and empty store shelves at a time when their own media show them the practical pleasures of living in the comparatively wealthy West. Outspoken reformists in and out of the recently elected <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputies have said the transition from the old system of central planning and control to a new market economy requires radical stripping away of bureaucratic control over supplies and prices. But <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> so far has talked about such steps without actually taking them. With the retirement of veteran Ukrainian party boss <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON>, 71, the 58-year-old <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is now the only member of the Politburo elevated to the ruling body during the regime of the late <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> has long been regarded as one of the most conservative forces in the leadership but too entrenched in his home republic for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to unseat him. Former <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON>, 66, another of those retired Wednesday, also was regarded as a conservative anchor who opposed many <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> reforms. The departures left one prominent conservative, <PERSON> Yegor </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>, in place. But both <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> have taken pains to express their support for each other while often disagreeing on policy. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> installed two of his own men, Gen. <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON>, the new <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> chief, and <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maslyukov </PERSON>, who heads economic planning, as full members of the Politburo, which now numbers 11 men. The retirements also included non-voting member <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Solovyev </PERSON>, who thus became the first member of the party's top leadership to fall after being defeated at the polls. <PERSON> Solovyev </PERSON>, who was rejected by the voters of <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> when he ran unopposed for a seat in the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, already had been removed as <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> party chief. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> opened the way for graceful retirement from the top echelons of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> power when he paid public tribute to <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON> as he relieved him of the presidency a year ago. He continued that practice Wednesday. When it was announced that <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON>, <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nikonov </PERSON> were going out on pension, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> thanked the three Politburo members warmly for their `` many years of fruitful activity'' in the party. Departures from the party leadership were once accomplished only by death or abrupt ouster into instant obscurity or public disgrace.
