<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A proposal to expand the rights of the disabled could put such a financial strain on city transit services that it ends up harming the general public and the handicapped alike, congressional critics of the legislation say. Republicans on a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee questioned Wednesday whether wheelchair lifts should be required on all public transit buses, pointing to one major city where existing lifts are used only every other day on average. A <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration official told the surface transportation subcommittee the provision is a key part of the Americans With Disabilities Act, which has come to be known as civil rights legislation for the handicapped. The universal use of the lifts, and a requirement for door-to-door bus service for those who ca n't make it to a bus stop, would help get the nation's 43 million disabled people into the mainstream of daily <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> life, said <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mross </PERSON>, deputy administrator of the <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. Republicans on the panel, however, are questioning the blanket nature of the requirements. `` I'm also concerned that if we increase costs to the point that we bring a reduction of service then we are not serving the disabled and we're not serving the general public either,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Bud </PERSON> <PERSON> Shuster </PERSON>, R-Pa. Each lift adds about $ 10,000 to $ 15,000 to the $ 155,000 cost of a bus and adds $ 2,000 to the annual maintenance cost, <PERSON> Mross </PERSON> told the panel He estimated the annual cost just of buying lifts at $ 30 million. <ORGANIZATION> UMTA </ORGANIZATION> would probably pay $ 24 million of that, he said. Although there are already regulations governing access by the elderly and handicapped to mass transit receiving federal funds, the new act would be far stricter. At issue in Wednesday's hearing was a requirement in the bill, already passed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and endorsed by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, that all public transit buses be equipped with wheelchair lifts. <PERSON> Shuster </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> figures show that in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, which has lift-equipped buses, each lift is used every other day. Spokesman for the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Cambria </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, systems _ which are considered leaders in serving the handicapped _ told the panel the bill would cause hardships. But <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Daly </PERSON>, legislative analyst at the President's <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> with </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disabilities </ORGANIZATION>, said the existing service keeps the handicapped virtually confined to their homes. She said many systems that have door-to-door service for the disabled require long advance notice _ 16 or 17 hours on the average _ and require a large amount of red tape to qualify for the service. `` You ca n't decide on a moment's notice that you want to go shopping or stay at the office late,'' she said. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed a version of the bill, with the transit requirements, on Sept. 7.
