<HEAD>Sexually Active College Students Not Using Condoms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A survey of 6,911 white, middle-class college students found that they knew how to protect themselves against AIDS and other sexually transmitted diseases but were n't doing it. About 75 percent of the Canadian students reported that they were sexually active but only 19 percent said they used condoms regularly. Twenty-six percent said they never used condoms. Yet 80 percent answered correctly when asked questions about preventing sexually transmitted diseases. The survey `` suggests most education and media campaigns to increase condom use are dismal failures,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Noni </PERSON> <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ottawa </ORGANIZATION>. She presented her findings Wednesday at a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Microbiology </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON>, a member of a Canadian health ministry task force on sexually transmitted diseases, said her findings probably would apply to white, middle-class <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> college students. `` If we've got it in ` middle-America <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>,' you must have it in middle <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' she said. The study found that 30 percent of 14-year-olds already had had intercourse. So had 77 percent of college men and 73 percent of college women. One in four men and one in eight women reported having had at least 10 sexual partners. These findings held true `` right across the country, coast-to-coast, little town, big town,'' said <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON>. A recent study of condom use by adolescent males in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> found that 57 percent reported use of a condom the last time they had intercourse, but that only 30 percent said they had always used a condom. The author of the American study, <PERSON> Freya </PERSON> <PERSON> Sonenstein </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said condom use has increased, but that condom use is lowest in the adolescents who are most at risk, either because they have multiple partners or have sex with prostitutes, for example. Condoms have been widely promoted as a way to cut the risk of getting infected with the human immunodeficiency virus, or HIV, that causes AIDS. But they also can protect against other sexually transmitted diseases, such as chlamydia, a common infection that can leave women infertile, sometimes without causing any symptoms at the time of infection. Eight percent of the Canadian college students have had at least one sexually transmitted disease, <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sonenstein </PERSON> found that reports of condom use among American adolescent males doubled during the past 10 years or so. Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> of the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> said condom sales jumped by 20 percent shortly after the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> surgeon general released his report on AIDS in 1986. Even so, syphilis is on the rise in inner cities. `` It appears obvious to me that there are a lot of people not using condoms that should,'' he said in a telephone interview. `` Clearly there is a large group of people putting themselves at risk for HIV by not using condoms.'' AIDS is uncommon among Canadian college students now, but `` with the rapidity with which they're having sexual intercourse, it would not take long to spread,'' <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON> said. She said that students must be taught not only the facts about AIDS and sexually transmitted diseases but also how to handle awkward social and sexual situations so that condom use becomes easier. `` When you teach someone how to drive a car, you do n't tell them about the engine, you teach them how to do it,'' she said.
</TEXT>
