<HEAD>Kremlin Dismayed at US Slowdown in Pace of Arms Control Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<UNK>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>'s journey to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for superpower negotiations comes at a time the Soviets are dealing with complex internal difficulties and talking as if the thrill is gone from relations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` That the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is not consumed by the enthusiastic wish to reach agreements with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is recognized even here as an indisputable fact,'' Pravda wrote from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, as <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> flew to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> and <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> last met in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in July, and for the Soviets, arms control remains the acid test of their relationship with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` Successful development of U.S.-Soviet relations can hardly be imagined without progress in the area of arms limitation and reduction,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency recently informed readers. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> and <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> will meet over the weekend in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hole </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyo </LOCATION>. The Kremlin's outward mood has shifted from elation to dismay as President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has presided over a slowdown in the pace of arms control talks, an area which gave <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> his first tangible policy achievement with the signing of a treaty with former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to eliminate medium - and shorter-range nuclear missiles For Soviets, whose dreary, shortage-plagued lot has failed to improve and in many cases worsened under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s economic reforms, the 1987 treaty and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s visit to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> seemed to presage a new and safer world, with a good share of credit going to their own leader. But with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the Soviets are dealing with a president who said this week he's in no hurry for a summit meeting with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. This time the Soviets have dropped heavy hints that <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> will unveil a new offer in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, where he pays a call on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> today, or later in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. Exactly what <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> is carrying remains under wraps, but <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> quoted him upon departure from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> as saying he has a personal message from <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on disarmament. `` It's a deep and constructive document'' designed to spur the talks in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said without giving details. Superpower negotiations aside, <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>'s activities before he boarded a special Washington-bound jetliner give a glimpse of how daunting the problems facing his country are. According to <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON>, his spokesman, the snowy-haired member of the ruling Politburo attended a <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> meeting charged with finding a way out of the spasms of violence between <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> ethnic groups in which 200 people have died in the last 19 months. In addition, entrenched portions of the Soviet bureaucracy, fearful of losing position and privilege, have resisted movement toward a more market-oriented economy with its attendant risks. Official press accounts assert the superpowers are within reach of an accord to boost a worldwide ban on chemical weapons, and <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> on Wednesday welcomed <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s statement that the Americans may withdraw their proposal for a ban on mobile ICBMs, one sticking point in the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> talks on long-range weapons. Yet the Soviets have expressed dissatisfaction with the pace of arms control talks under the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. Usually smiling and debonair, <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> earlier this month denounced the `` constraint and timidity'' of the officials in charge of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s new arms reduction policy. It was another signal of the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>'s frustration at the latest turn taken by U.S.-Soviet relations. Putting superpower talks for a 50 percent reduction of strategic weapons on a faster track is a major concern of the Soviets, and they've all but openly accused <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> of neglecting the parleys. `` The <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> negotiations and the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> delegation's stance there call for a powerful political impetus,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. `` Only the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> president and the secretary of state are able to provide it.'' `` When creating the atmosphere around the forthcoming political contacts, the Soviet side would like to concentrate primarily on recent positive statements by President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Among those statements is <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s professed support for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s domestic reform agenda, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said Whatever the course of the talks, <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> should feel right at home in the mountain air of <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hole </LOCATION>. His native <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> in the Soviet south lies in the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> range, and its tallest peak, <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elbrus </ORGANIZATION>, tops Grand Teton by almost a mile.
