<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-WinnersandLosers     09-21 0842</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Winners and Losers,0861</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Politburo Strongly Pro-Gorbachev ^With PM-Soviet-Power Play,
Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The makeup of the Soviet Politburo has shifted sharply and now reflects strong support of President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms. The Communist Party's ruling body Wednesday retired its last <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> man, die-hard conservative <LOCATION> Ukrainian </LOCATION> party leader <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON>, and the first <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader to lose a public vote of confidence, former <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> party chief <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solovyov </PERSON>. Key <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> supporters also joined the Politburo: <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maslyukov </PERSON>, the man appointed to decentralize economic planning; <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> chief who spent his career in the secret police force's foreign operations rather than in repression of domestic dissent; and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> adviser, <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Primakov </PERSON>, who also is a leader in the new Soviet legislature. The Politburo also lost one KGB general and gained two with the retirement of former <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON> and the promotion of <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pugo </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WINNERS</NOTE>
<NOTE>Promoted to full Politburo membership</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maslyukov </PERSON>, 52, named last year to transform the Soviet central planning agency, <LOCATION> Gosplan </LOCATION>, from a vast bureaucracy trying to control the production and distribution of every nut and bolt to a smaller agency that only sets general economic goals. He is a Russian born in <LOCATION> Tadzhikistan </LOCATION> who held jobs in engineering and the defense industry for 26 years. He took on the decentralization of the Soviet economy in 1988, replacing <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Talyzin </PERSON>, who lost his non-voting status on the Politburo on Wednesday. <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON>, 65, a career spy promoted to run the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> last year and the first <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> chairman to face a public confirmation hearing this summer. He is a Russian schooled in law and diplomacy and ran foreign spy operations for years. As KBG chairman he has launched a publicity campaign emphasizing the agency's role in capturing foreign spies and terrorists while playing down its role in repressing dissidents.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Promoted to non-voting Politburo membership</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Primakov </PERSON>, 59, a <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> expert elected chairman of one of the houses of the Soviet legislature in June. He could play an important role in pushing <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms through the legislislature. He is a Russian who started his career as a government official overseeing broadcasting. He has worked in government think tanks since 1970. <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pugo </PERSON>, 52, the youngest member of the Politburo. He is a Latvian <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> general whose Bolshevik father is believed to have been imprisoned by <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> in the purges of the 1930s. He served as head of the Latvian <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> before becoming party chief in <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> in 1984. Many Latvian activists were happy to see him replaced last year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LOSERS</NOTE>
<NOTE>Retired from full membership on the Politburo</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON>, 71, Ukrainian party chief. Many Ukrainian reformers blame him for stifling dissent and holding back <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s economic reforms in the nation's breadbasket. <PERSON> Shcherbitsky </PERSON> lost his first three attempts to win nomination to the new <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputies in his capital, <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>. He is Ukrainian, an engineer and lifelong party bureaucrat. <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON>, 66, the former <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> chief who last year was promoted to the Politburo and given the job of running the criminal justice system. A Russian, he worked as an engineer for two years before moving to party jobs in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>. He was deputy chairman and then chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> from 1968 to 1988 during two decades of crackdowns on dissidents. <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nikonov </PERSON>, 60, a agricultural and party bureaucrat. He is a Russian who moved to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> as deputy minister of agriculture in 1979. In last year's Politburo shake-up, he became <PERSON> Yegor </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>'s deputy in the party commission on agriculture.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Retired from non-voting membership on the Politburo</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solovyov </PERSON>, 65, the <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> regional party chief who despite running unopposed lost election to a seat in the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last spring when more than 50 percent of the voters crossed his name off the ballot. Reformers in the <ORGANIZATION> Leningrad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> successfully demanded his removal from the party leadership. A Russian, he spent 22 years as a subway construction engineer in <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> before moving to party work in 1974. <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Talyzin </PERSON>, 60, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s first choice for planning chief in 1985, who was demoted last year when the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> opted for more radical decentralization of the economy. The <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> engineer who moved into government through the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> has.
