<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Panicked residents and tourists who scrambled to the first evacuation plane out of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Croix </LOCATION> told tales of horror after arriving back on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mainland. Hurricane Hugo's devastation of the popular Caribbean tourist retreat was followed by a swarm of gun-wielding looters, prompting President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to dispatch military police and arrange for evacuations. `` We just got lucky,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> McManus </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, about being among 145 passengers on a special <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> evacuation flight arranged by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marshals Wednesday night. He said the sight of the plane at the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Croix </LOCATION> airport touched off a stampede of those trying to flee. `` The looters were everywhere there,'' said <PERSON> McManus </PERSON>, still gripping the 4-iron golf club he used for protection. `` They said, ` We're in charge now.' At one grocery store, they just rolled up trucks and loaded them up.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Brotman </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Camden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, who was on temporary assignment in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Croix </LOCATION>, said he first had to protect himself from the storm, then the looters. `` It was the most devastating experience of my life,'' <PERSON> Brotman </PERSON> said. `` We had three originally in our condomimium, and after the storm there were 18 in one room with mattresses up against every wall and rope to hold the shutters closed.'' <PERSON> Nadine </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON>, owner of an art gallery in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Croix </LOCATION>, said she fled to protect her 5-month-old son from violence several evacuee