<HEAD>New Island Residents Taking Hurricane Seriously</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `The weather ...' to UPDATE chances of hurricane
hitting island.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUNSWICK, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Many residents of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Simons </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> never lived through a major hurricane, but they're not ignoring the furor of Hurricane Hugo as it headed toward the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. `` I think anybody is going to be worried. It's a major catastrophic happening,'' said <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Cullens </PERSON>, a director of the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Simons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. At an island grocery store, shoppers packed carts with bottled water, canned goods and other supplies. `` Compared to past storms, they're taking it more seriously,'' supermarket manager <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said. `` A lot more people seem to be talking about leaving.'' Attracted by its beaches, golf courses, warm climate and Southern charm, about 5,000 people have moved to the island 65 miles south of <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> since the last hurricane came ashore in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> in 1979. <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simons </PERSON> is about 10 miles long and is connected to the mainland city of <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION> by a seven-mile causeway. Parts of the island remain undeveloped but elsewhere, beachfront condos and subdivisions have sprouted up amid palms, pines and moss-draped oaks. Disaster officials called for the voluntary evacuation of the island's 14,000 residents late Wednesday. They were ready to order the evacuation of 30,000 residents from St. <PERSON> Simons </PERSON> and lowlying areas of <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION> and surrounding <LOCATION> Glynn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. `` We would have to assess the situation, look at the tides, the storm surge and the advice of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Stelle </PERSON>, the county's community development director. The weather service issued a hurricane watch Wednesday evening and said there was an 11 percent chance <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> could come within 65 miles of <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> between 8 p.m. today and 8 a.m. Friday. When Hurricane <PERSON> David </PERSON> came ashore near <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> on Sept. 4, 1979, the storm knocked down trees, power lines and flooded streets before moving into <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. <PERSON> David </PERSON> left 1,200 people dead _ 19 in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> has claimed 25 lives on <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> islands. Since its last hurricane, <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simons </PERSON>' population jumped from 9,000. `` The major problem is the education of people,'' said <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Coastal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION>. `` We've got a lot of new people who probably are n't familiar with coastal problems associated with a hurricane. They're now aware of the warnings and what the warnings mean.'' The problem is common in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>'s eight coastal counties. The area is the state's fastest growing region, with the population surging from 350,000 in 1980 to an estimated 400,000 in 1988. Growth has been spurred by a new submarine base in <LOCATION> Camden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, an <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> division at <LOCATION> Hinesville </LOCATION>, an $ 800-million-a-year tourist industry and an influx of industries. But <ORGANI