<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar remained sharply lower against the Japanese yen Thursday, while the key index on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> rose. The dollar closed at 145.00 yen, down 1.25 yen from Wednesday's close of 146.25 yen It started trading lower at 144.90 yen and moved between 144.82 yen and 145.25 yen. The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shot up 274.44 points, or 0.80 percent, ending the day at 34,745.02. It had lost 0.49 points the previous day. The index rose as market players were reassured by the yen's rebound against the dollar, and buying orders for a variety of issues were given since the opening, said <PERSON> Masahiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Umemori </PERSON>, a stock analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> `` Participants were buying supermarket issues considering that reorganization and easing regulations on large-scale retail stores could be positive steps to improve U.S.-Japan structural problems,'' he said. In currency dealings, the dollar's drop followed an overnight downswing on overseas markets over speculation that <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> may raise the country's interest rates. A dealer with the Bank of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> said Japanese market players were watching closely whether the West German <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> will take action on its interest rates during its scheduled meeting Thursday. Although institutional investors and trading houses bought the dollar as it fell, the majority of participants slowed down their dollar-buying ahead of the monetary talks in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> this weekend among the <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION> industrialized nations, which might come up with some measure to stem the dollar's strength, said the dealer, speaking on condition of 