<FIRST>r w PM-MissingMercedes     09-21 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missing Mercedes,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mercedes Pulls Disappearing Act on EPA Guzzlers List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>'s massive annual guide to automobile gas mileage is supposed to tell motorists at a glance what cars are the stingiest and the worst guzzlers of fuel. But not always, it turns out. Dozens of cars each year are missing from the annual list, and this year the absent included the entire line of luxury cars from <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION>, including 11 whose mileage is so poor the cars are subject to the special `` guzzler'' excise tax. Three of the Mercedes cars likely would have made the `` ten worst'' list had they been included in the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> survey of 981 cars that was released earlier this week and widely distributed by the news media. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Larson </PERSON>, branch manager at the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s auto testing laboratory in <LOCATION> Ann </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arbor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, said every year perhaps 80 or 90 cars do not make the list because manufacturers do not provide the testing data to the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> when the mileage guide goes to the printer. Aside from Mercedes, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> could not say what specific cars were missing. A spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> still must submit test data for three cars and industry sources said they would not be surprised if a dozen or more other manufacturers had yet to submit test information on a few cars each. `` There are always a few stragglers,'' said <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>. Federal law requires automakers to submit the mileage test data and have it certified by the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> before a car is placed on the market. But they are not required to submit the information by a specific date or meet the deadline for the initial industry-wide mileage guide. Government and industry sources, speaking anonymously, acknowledged the mileage guide can both help and hinder automakers. Manufacturers often test their high mileage cars early to meet the deadline for the publication and move more slowly on their high-mileage models, said one official. The submission of the test data `` is at the manufacturer's control I do n't know what was in the minds of Mercedes in making their decision -LRB- not to submit test results earlier -RRB-. But they do have relatively fuel inefficient vehicles,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Larson </PERSON>. The deadline for test data this year was Aug. 30. At the request of one automaker, it was postponed until Sept. 5. <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION> submitted its first 1990 model test data covering a dozen cars on Sept. 9, said <PERSON> Eldert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bontekoe </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s certification office in <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON>. A.B. <PERSON> Shuman </PERSON>, manager of public relations at <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Montvale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, said in a telephone interview the mileage performance of the cars was `` absolutely not a factor'' in the data being submitted late. `` It was just getting it all done,'' said <PERSON> Shuman </PERSON>, who said the company had been unable to complete all the testing in time. <PERSON> Shuman </PERSON> also noted Mercedes does not put its 1990 models on the market until Nov. 1 and so has more time to submit the test data than many other automakers whose 1990 models hit the showroom in September and October. Nevertheless, 11 of the Mercedes cars showed overall mileage of 18 miles per gallon or less and are subject to a `` gas guzzler'' excise tax, according to figures provided by the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>. At least three of the 1990 Mercedes models had mileage so low they likely would have been among the `` worst ten'' in mileage for 1990 had they been included in the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> survey list. The mileage data for the Mercedes cars _ along with figures for any other cars submitted late _ will be included in an updated mileage list in February. But Ms. <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman, acknowledged the revised list usually gets little public attention.
