 at $ 300 million for each of the three years; the fund for <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> at $ 75 million a year. House Democrats also indicated their willingness on Wednesday to substantially increase aid to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. `` I believe we should give the administration everything it has asked for _ and then do more,'' Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` If we do not come to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s aid, how can we expect others to make the sacrifices necessary to obtain freedom and democracy? Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mo </LOCATION>., the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> majority leader, said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must find ways to rise above the nation's budget crunch and provide assistance to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> equal to the historic nature of their apparent transformation from communist rule `` Now is not the time for the niceties of bookkeeping; now is the time for imagination and innovation,'' <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> said. `` Visionaries do not wear green eyeshades.'' Acting on amendments to the overall foreign aid bill, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted Wednesday to boost aid to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> to $ 90 million after appeals to give the country's new president `` a chance to succeed.'' Voting 67-33, the legislators removed from the bill a provision that would have cut the aid into three installments to be made available at four-month intervals, with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> given virtual veto power over the last installment. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> then voted to peg <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LO