5. The women, all severely incapacitated and many suffering from Alzheimer's disease, were killed between January and April 1987. Defense attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Piazza </PERSON> said he planned to ask the judge to set aside the verdict. `` I'm surprised and disappointed,'' <PERSON> Piazza </PERSON> said. `` There was no physical evidence whatsoever.'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, testifying Tuesday, denied that any murders had occurred at the home and said the murder plot was nothing more than a joke made up by <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> that had gotten out of hand. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said a jealous <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> went to police with the story after <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> left her for another lover and moved to her hometown of <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Her denials contradicted testimony of several former co-workers and friends who said she admitted suffocating patients at Alpine Manor. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>'s former lover, <PERSON> Heather </PERSON> <PERSON> Baragar </PERSON>, testified that <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> often confessed to her and would `` joke around about it.'' Another woman testified <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> had shown her `` souvenirs,'' such as an anklet and a balloon, they said they had taken from their victims. <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> testified that she stood watch while <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> suffocated one patient, but lacked the nerve to kill any of the patients herself. The deaths had been ruled natural, and no autopsies were performed. Police began investigating last October after <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>'s ex-husband told them she had confessed her part in the murder plot Autopsies were performed on the only two bodies that were not cremated, but no definitive evidence of suffocation was found. `` Even though we still find it difficult to believe that any of this actually happened ... we will continue to place our trust in our system of justice,'' said a statement from the nursing home. In his closing arguments, Assistant Kent County Prosecutor <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Schieber </PERSON> speculated that <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> herself may not know why she killed the women. `` It was murder for its own pleasure,'' he said.
