<TEXT>
 The dollar rose against all major currencies in nervous European trading early today amid signs <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> will not raise interest rates before a weekend meeting of the world's leading industrialized nations Gold prices fell. Dealers said they expected the dollar to trade within a narrow range before today's scheduled meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. Many market players expected the West German central bank to take no immediate action on interest rates, despite signs of rising inflation, before monetary talks open Saturday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> among the Group of Seven industrialized nations. The absence of <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> from the meeting also reduced the chances of a rate hike, dealers said. The G-7 nations are the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar fell to a closing 145.00 Japanese yen from 146.25 yen at Wednesday's close. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it edged back up to 145.10 yen. Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Wednesday: _ 1.9442 West German marks, up from 1.9400 _ 1.6835 Swiss francs, up from 1.6800 _ 6.5717 French francs, up from 6.5585 _ 2.1903 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1890 _ 1,402.00 Italian lire, up from 1,399.50 _ 1.1825 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1824 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound fell to $ 1.5795 Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 363.65 a troy ounce, up from $ 363.25 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 362.95. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 363.35, down from $ 363.50 bid late Wednesday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose $ 2.69 to a closing bid of $ 364.11. Silver bullion rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a bid price of $ 5.13 troy ounce, up from $ 5.09 bid late Wednesday.
