<HEAD>Miami Superintendent to Head New York's Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>, who grew up in a <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> housing project and dropped out of a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> high school, never dreamed he would lead the nation's largest public school system. <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>, currently the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> school superintendent, said the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> job was the farthest thing from his mind when he was growing up in `` rough areas'' on <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s west side. `` I did n't think I'd leave <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> alive, much less come back to lead the school system,'' he said at a news conference in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. On Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> voted unanimously to approve <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> as the next chancellor of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> public schools. `` He will stand as a splendid role model,'' board President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said of 53-year-old <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>. <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> praised <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> for lowering the dropout rate in <LOCATION> Miami-Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> schools while increasing parent and student involvement in individual schools. <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> will face a daunting list of problems in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, including overcrowded schools, a high dropout rate and a decentralized system which has been stung by patronage and corruption scandals. `` I like a challenge,'' said <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>. `` If you put well-intentioned people together, people with their hearts in the right place, I think they can do something for the kids.'' <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> said <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> would start in January or February and would be paid $ 195,000 a year under an 18-month contract. The salary is $ 40,000 more than <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> receives in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and $ 45,000 more than the previous chancellor, the late <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, was paid. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION>, which represents 102,000 teachers, assistants, counselors, psychologists and secretaries in the city's schools, praised <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> for emphasizing `` school-based management and shared decision making.'' <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> said that before <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> took over <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s schools, there were two applicants for each teaching vacancy. Now there are six. <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> was one of three finalists in the search that began after <PERSON> Green </PERSON> died of an asthma attack in May. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> `` Bud'' <PERSON> Spillane </PERSON>, superintendent of schools in <LOCATION> Fairfax </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, was interviewed by the board Tuesday and <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Prophet </PERSON>, school superintendent of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, withdrew from consideration. In 1987, during the search that was to lead to <PERSON> Green </PERSON>'s appointment, the board had asked <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> to apply for the job But <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> said the timing was wrong because he had just been named to head the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> system, the nation's fourth biggest. Asked why he said yes this time, <P