<HEAD>American Professors Incorporate Events of Tiananmen Square into Courses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Many American professors are including the recent democracy protests in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and subsequent army crackdown in their courses, and they're finding that the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> massacre has boosted student interest in those courses sharply. Some professors already have begun to teach the lessons of Tiananmen Square this fall while others plan to wait until spring to review the already rich literature spawned by the protests. `` Five or six years after our students graduate, many of them are in positions to make a difference,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Walder </PERSON>, a professor of sociology at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Walder </PERSON> usually teaches a graduate seminar focusing on post-1949 events in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> but plans this year to examine the years just since 1979. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, a professor of government at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, said the demonstrations for democracy that occupied <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s Tiananmen Square until the army crackdown in early June will form the `` centerpiece'' of a survey of Chinese politics he plans to teach next spring. `` It relates to every thesis of political change in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said, `` That is, whether <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> authoritarianism was capable of significant economic reform while suppressing political change or alternatively, whether the decade of economic reform in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was forced.'' <PERSON> Roderick </PERSON> <PERSON> MacFarquhar </PERSON>, professor of government at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, plans to teach a seminar in Chinese politics to juniors this semester and said that the June protests will take up at least one week of the course. <PERSON> MacFarquhar </PERSON> said he heard from colleagues at <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> when he taught a course on the Cultural Revolution several years ago that <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> officials `` wondered why someone at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> was giving a course on it and they were n't. It caused a lively debate.'' As a result, <PERSON> MacFarquhar </PERSON> said the current regime may well be apprised of professors at American universities teaching about Tiananmen Square `` but since they are antagonistic, the reaction at the official level will be negative.'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Gold </PERSON>, associate professor of sociology and vice-chairman of the Center for Chinese Studies at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, said the number of students enrolled in his undergraduate course on contemporary Chinese society has doubled to more than 120 students since he last offered it two years ago. But while Gold expects that the student protests will dominate the course, he said recent events in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> reflected a pattern in <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government and society that has existed for centuries. `` It's part of a dichotomy, between a tightening up and a loosening, that goes back thousands of years,'' <PERSON> Gold </PERSON> said. `` But Tiananmen Square meant a temporary victory for those people who want to clamp down. What happened in <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> has happened many times. Part of the tragedy is how little is new,'' he said. <PERSON> Gold </PERSON> said the events in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> `` caught the imagination'' of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> students. `` It brought out our respect for human rights and democracy that most people do n't think of very often,'' he said. `` When they saw this in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> it was sort of an ennobling experience. People are trying to understand what happened and once they do it will have a larger impact.''
