<HEAD>Military Head Denies Censorship at Pacific Stars and Stripes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECT style on Stars and Stripes, which does not have an ampersand.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The military head of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> edition of Stars and Stripes today rejected allegations of censorship and personnel abuse under his editorship of the newspaper for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> armed forces in the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. `` The paper is not censored,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Col. <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>. `` I've never had anyone, no flag officer or bureaucrat, tell me what stories to write or how they are to run. `` I've been here three years and no one has told me anything like that.'' But a civilian journalist at the newspaper, <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON> <PERSON> Brackett </PERSON>, said he was preparing a list of serious problems to be given to the paper's management and to ombusdman <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foisie </PERSON>, who is to arrive Sunday. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> appointed <PERSON> Foisie </PERSON> ombudsman in June for the European and Far East editions of Stars and Stripes, with authority to monitor their performance and argue with military brass over decisions about news coverage. He is a former editor with <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> and a former executive editor of the Paris-based <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>. `` The issue is not simply censorship. It is also abuse of personnel and editorial mismanagement,'' <PERSON> Brackett </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. <PERSON> Brackett </PERSON>, who testified before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last winter about conditions at the newspaper, declined to give details before the list is submitted. <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>, who also testified before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on the dispute, said in a telephone interview that he felt <PERSON> Foisie </PERSON> also will represent him. `` Mr. <PERSON> Foisie </PERSON> will have the opportunity to speak with whomever he wishes, and I'm confident he will come to the conclusion we're not censoring the paper,'' he said. The editorial staff consists of 17 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> civilians and 21 military people, <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> disputed <PERSON> Brackett </PERSON>'s claim that <PERSON> Brackett </PERSON> had been disciplined for testifying to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Brackett </PERSON> has been only temporarily relieved as <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> editor and assigned to be a supervising editor, <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> said, `` while we can analyze the latest series of allegations.'' He said it was normal for civilian employees of the government to be relieved of normal duties during an investigation. <PERSON> Brackett </PERSON> said, however, `` I feel my relief is harassment and definitely retribution for having testified to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Brackett </PERSON>, 49, said he was a retired <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> officer with about 20 years experience in journalism and in the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. There have been a series of disputes involving Stars and Stripes in recent years and they predate the arrival of <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>, who previously was a staff officer in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Reporters who have worked for Star and Stripes say their reporting of the news sometimes suffers because military commanders worry about the sensitivities of host countries. The two editions of the paper, published in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, are edited separately and are supposed to be `` hometown newspapers'' for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> service personnel. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> describes them as `` authorized, but unofficial publications'' and their charter says they are to provide `` a free flow of news and information ... without censorship or news management.'' But last year an investigation by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, an arm of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, found evidence of censorship and improper managament. The <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Professional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journalists </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Sigma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chi </ORGANIZATION>, assisted in that investigation. Democratic Reps. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Boxer </PERSON> of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutto </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> have written to Adm. <PERSON> Huntington </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardisty </PERSON>, commander of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, asking him to look into continued allegations. `` What we have here is harassment of whistle-blowers and censorship,'' Ms. <PERSON> Boxer </PERSON> said in an interview in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` It's bad enough to censor the news Our men and women in uniform deserve the news as all of us get it, as harsh as it is.''
