<HEAD>Aircraft Explodes at Base; Two Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRBANKS, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> tanker aircraft exploded and burned at <ORGANIZATION> Eielson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, killing two people, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said. The five others aboard received minor injuries. Sgt. <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> LaDoucer </PERSON> said the KC-135 plane apparently was taxiing to park when the explosion occurred at about 3 p.m. Wednesday. The fire, which destroyed the plane, was reported out within two hours. Two base firefighters also were treated for minor injuries, officials said. The cause of the explosion was not immediately known. An <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> board will investigate the incident, <PERSON> LaDoucer </PERSON> said. Five of the seven people aboard were crew members, and the two others were military passengers, <PERSON> LaDoucer </PERSON> said. Names were withheld. The plane, used for in-flight refueling, was returning from a routine training mission, Sgt. <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. He said he did not know how much fuel was aboard. The Boeing-built aircraft, 134 feet long and with a windowless fuselage, was part of the 168th <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refueling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Squadron </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Eielson </ORGANIZATION>.
