<HEAD>Survivors Take Rescue Slide, Land in Water</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Flight 5050...' to UPDATE with passenger number
revised to 63, sted 61, all accounted for.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-USAir Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Passengers aboard a <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> jet that crashed into the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> said they were surprised when they landed in the water after sliding down chutes from the plane, and clung to driftwood until being rescued. `` Everyone was saying, ` Get out! Get out! Get out!' So we started helping each other get out,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, a social worker from <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> who was on the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 with his wife, <PERSON> Valerie </PERSON>. `` They told us to get of the plane and go out the door. I thought we were going to go down the slide and onto the runway. When we got off the slide we were in the water.'' Flight 5050, from <LOCATION> LaGuardia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, was carrying 63 people when it skidded off a runway into the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, killing two people, the airline said. `` It was n't a violent crash,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, 25, of <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. `` We went out the emergency exit. There was some driftwood'' in the water that several people clung to. He said police came by in a boat and picked them up. `` We were just hanging on to each other. We decided the only thing to do was to be calm.'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawthorne </PERSON>, a CBS News producer who was on the flight, said via a cellular telephone that the engines apparently were cut halfway down the runway and went into reverse thrust. `` At that time no one thought there was going to be real trouble,'' he said. `` The pilot seemed to be accelerating but did n't have enough power to get the plane up,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said as he and his wife huddled in blankets inside an airport terminal. `` And it seemed something happened and he put on the brakes,'' he said. `` The plane took a dip and the next thing I knew all hell broke loose.'' <PERSON> Hawthorne </PERSON> said he managed to get out onto a wing, where he waited with several other people to be rescued. `` A lot of women and children were screaming that they could n't swim, they could n't swim,'' he said `` Most people were pretty calm after we got out onto the wing of the plane,'' he said. `` And they waited for boats to come pick us up and the rescuers also arrived and I have to say they did a pretty good job of keeping everybody calm and getting them safely off.'' Some people were trapped in the tail section of the plane, he said, and rescuers and crewmembers tried to keep them calm. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Murtha </PERSON>, a fire department scuba diver, said it took him about 45 minutes using a metal cutter to rescue one woman trapped in the tail section between collapsed seats, behind a woman who had died. `` Water started coming into the tail section,'' he said. `` When we started it was at 6 inches and when we finished there was 3 feet. And it -LRB- the fuselage -RRB- was rocking.'' He said firefighters placed the unidentified woman, who was not seriously injured, into a basket and took her to a boat. `` She hugged us, kissed us. She wanted to know our names. She thanked us a million times,'' <PERSON> Murtha </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said a stranger helped him after they hit the water. `` I started to panic,'' he said. `` There was a guy. ... He grabbed me, he maneuvered me over to the driftwood. If it was n't there I do n't know what would have happened.
