<HEAD>Bush Rejects Coffee Quota Appeal From Colombia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is refusing a request by Colombian President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> to reinstate a one-year <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> coffee export that has been beneficial to Colombian farmers, the White House says. <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s coffee earnings have slumped at the same time that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is seeking Barco's help in cracking down on cocaine exports. Colombian officials have suggested they will have an even harder time persuading hard-pressed <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> farmers to grow coffee instead of coca if coffee export prices continue to slip. Colombian coffee prices have fallen sharply since the 74-nation International Coffee Agreement -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> ICA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ to which both the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> belonged _ collapsed in July after the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> pulled out in a dispute over prices with coffee-producing nations. The Agreement set quotas for member nations' exports aimed at supporting prices of beans at $ 1.20 per pound or more. Some Central American and others, supported by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, wanted larger quotas. After suspension of the quotas in early July, prices fell quickly to around 85 cents per pound, give or take a few pennies. <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> has said this will cost $ 500 million a year in export revenue. <PERSON> Barco </PERSON>, whose nation relies on coffee as a major source of export earnings, had appealed to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to reconsider the coffee decision and to support reinstating the quotas for at least one year. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Barco </ORGANIZATION>, said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was ready to negotiate for a new quota system but was unwilling to adhere to the now-defunct agreement, presidential press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said Wednesday. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s letter to <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> was one `` expressing appreciation of the importance of coffee to the economies of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and other developing countries.'' The letter, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> continued, `` expressed his -LRB- <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s -RRB- disappointment that the members of the <ORGANIZATION> ICA </ORGANIZATION> were unable to settle ... two fundamental problems.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wanted an increase in export quotas for higher-quality coffees enjoyed by American consumers, and tough penalties against countries secretly selling coffee surpluses to Eastern Bloc nations at prices below those charged the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> expresses his confidence that a lasting solution which is acceptable to other major members and respects market trends can be found,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said.
