<HEAD>German Prosecutor to Check British Documents on Former Nazi General</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUEBECK, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The prosecutor's office said today it is sending a lawyer to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> next week to study evidence against a former Nazi SS general suspected in the deaths of 85 British war prisoners in 1940. The <LOCATION> Luebeck </LOCATION> prosecutor's office opened a new investigation of ex-Gen. <PERSON> Wilhelm </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohnke </PERSON>, 78, in June 1988 after the British <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said it had discovered more survivors of the massacre `` One of our prosecutor's will be in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> early next week to evaluate documents held there as part of the on-going <PERSON> Mohnke </PERSON> investigation,'' prosecutor's spokesman <PERSON> Joachim </PERSON> <PERSON> Boettcher </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. He identified the prosecutor being sent as <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON> <PERSON> Nigendank </PERSON>. <PERSON> Boettcher </PERSON> said <PERSON> Mohnke </PERSON> remains free in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> pending results of the investigation. <PERSON> Mohnke </PERSON> allegedly gave orders in 1940 for 85 unarmed British prisoners being held in a barn to be shot by SS troops at <LOCATION> Wormhoudt </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Dunkirk </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. A similar investigation of <PERSON> Mohnke </PERSON> was dropped in 1973 for lack of evidence. Earlier probes of <PERSON> Mohnke </PERSON>'s alleged involvement in the 1944 execution of 75 unarmed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prisoners of war at <LOCATION> Malmedy </LOCATION>, in the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ardennes </LOCATION>, and Canadians in <LOCATION> Normandy </LOCATION> the same year, also were dropped for lack of evidence. <PERSON> Mohnke </PERSON>, a retired businessman who lives in the town of <LOCATION> Stemwarde </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Hamburg </LOCATION>, repeatedly has denied any connection with the massacres.
