<HEAD>10 Bombs Explode, Damaging Political Offices and a Bank</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 17 grafs to UPDATE with party publishing names of
officials denied U.S. visas. Pickup 14th pvs, `As part...' Minor editing
thereafter.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Barrio Escobar, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ten bombs exploded early today in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, causing heavy damage to nine offices of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s main political parties and to one bank, police said. At least two people were reported injured. Bombings have occurred almost daily since the government declared a crackdown on <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s powerful cocaine traffickers on Aug. 18. The explosions came hours after lawmakers urged the government to publicize reported `` black lists'' of corrupt politicians and officials. Colombian newspapers today published the names of 25 lawmakers and politicians, including a <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> presidential candidate, who the papers said had their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> visas denied or canceled. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Urutia </PERSON> today said he did not know if the visas were withheld because of links with traffickers. He refused further comment. Police said the bombs went off around 3 a.m. They damaged offices of the Liberals and Conservatives, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s two main political parties, in several neighborhoods of the capital of 6 million people. Another blast ripped through a bank. Banks have been a favorite target of the cocaine cartels. Police said the two injured people were taken to hospitals. There were no other details immediately available. `` This shows the total decadence we are living in in this country. It's a senseless war,'' said <PERSON> Emilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barguch </PERSON>, secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. He said one blast destroyed national party headquarters. <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> mayor, called for an emergency meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to discuss additional security measures. <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> presidential candidate <PERSON> Alberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Santofimio </PERSON> <PERSON> Botero </PERSON> said today his <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> visa was canceled in March in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> because he met <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> cartel leader <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Escobar </PERSON> eight years ago, when both were congressmen. `` I barely knew him and met him only during a political rally,'' the Liberal politician told <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caracol </ORGANIZATION>, a private radio chain. He accused the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of retaliating for his criticism of `` American intervention in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and other parts of <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' On Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> asked the government for a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> list with names of politicians denied visas because of suspected drug connections. It also passed a resolution urging the government to make public other lists with names of politicians and government leaders alleged to have links with the cartels. <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> has said he's not aware of any such lists. Also Wednesday, the head of the country's criminal investigation office said <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> mercenaries smuggled weapons through <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to train assassination squads for drug cartels, teaching them tactics used in political killings and bombings. Gen. <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Maza </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquez </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administrative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> that the mercenaries, working for the drug cartels since 1987, `` ca n't escape responsibility'' for the bank bombings and political assassinations. The slaying Aug. 18 of Sen. <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Galan </PERSON>, a popular presidential candidate and anti-drug crusader, led to the government crackdown. As part of the crackdown, President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> revived <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s extradition treaty with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, where the top traffickers are wanted. So far, one person has been extradited, but the drug barons on the nation's most-wanted list have eluded capture. <PERSON> Maza </PERSON> said foreign military trainers smuggled weapons from neighboring <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to train four paramilitary groups. Squads of 50 to 80 men each received up to four months of training, <PERSON> Maza </PERSON> said. He said at least nine Israelis trained the squads. It's unknown how many British mercenaries were involved, but the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> has acknowledged trainers were in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Maza </PERSON> said his information was based in `` intelligence investigations,'' but he charged that many in the military and government, in an attempt to discredit him, and have been slow to act on his reports. <PERSON> Maza </PERSON>, who has had at least four recent attempts on his life, headed the investigation that led to the government issuing an arrest warrant Monday for <PERSON> Yair </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, a former Israeli army colonel accused of training paramilitary squads for drug cartels. Mercenary training for both the <LOCATION> Cali </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> cocaine cartels consisted of supplying weapons and martial arts and explosives training, <PERSON> Maza </PERSON> said.
