<FIRST>u w PM-DeathPenalty     09-21 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Death Penalty,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Proposes Streamlining of Death Penaly Appeals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A special committee today proposed streamlining death penalty appeals to assure swifter executions but only after guaranteeing condemned prisoners competent legal help. `` Capital cases should be subject to one complete and fair course of collateral review in the state and federal system,'' said the panel appointed by Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON>. `` When this review has concluded, litigation should end.'' Retired Supreme Court Justice <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, the committee chairman, said the current system encourages endless delays, repetitive appeals and frenzied, last-minute activity as death row inmates approach scheduled executions. `` The hard fact is that the laws of 37 states -LRB- that have the death penalty -RRB- are not being enforced by the courts,'' <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said. `` I respect those who argue for outright abolition of death punishment. But it seems irrational to retain the penalty and frustrate its fair implementation.'' <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> noted that there are some 2,200 death row inmates but there have been only 118 executions since the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> reinstated the death penalty in 1972. He said the average delay between conviction and execution is more than eight years and the longest has been 14 -LCB- years. `` Delay of this magnitude is hardly necessary for fairness or for thorough review,'' <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said. The committee he heads recommended that states enact laws to assure that death row inmates have adequate legal help throughout their appeals at taxpayer expense. The committee did not estimate the potential cost or the likely reduction in time between convictions and executions. If the state chose not to adopt the plan, the current system would remain in effect for that state _ permitting repetitive state and federal court appeals. One feature of the new system would be a six-month period to file a federal appeal after the prisoner exhausts state appeals. There is no such time period now. The current system permits death row inmates to file repeated appeals to federal courts to challenge alleged violations of their constitutional rights. Under the committee's proposal, there would be one round of such federal appeals unless condemned prisoners could produce new evidence to demonstrate innocence.
</TEXT>
