<HEAD>Thatcher Urges Western Support for Soviet Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Quayle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> called today for strong Western support for Soviet economic and political reforms, saying they are in the interest of liberty. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for an international conference of conservative parties, also said she is confident that trade issues raised in meetings with Japanese leaders and business executives will be resolved satisfactorily. The <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> leader has frankly criticized what she called <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s unfair trade barriers and urged fast action to open its markets to foreign goods In a meeting with former Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> and later in comments to reporters, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> stressed <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s responsibility to contribute to global economic growth and called for stronger support for reforms spearheaded by Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> `` This is the most bold and courageous leader the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has had while it's been under Communism. What Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is attempting to do ... is in the interests of liberty as a whole and in the interest of all other nations who believe in the cause of democracy as well. `` We should do, therefore, everything we can to support this great, historic movement ... and do all we can to see that it is successful.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> will visit <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for talks with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> when she leaves <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> on Friday. She noted a trend in favor of <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> democratic political and economic views but cautioned against relaxing defenses, predicting a period of instability in East-West relations and elsewhere. `` A time of great uncertainty is no time to reduce your defenses,'' she said. `` You do n't prevent wars by disarmament. You prevent wars by quietly being prepared and having a sure defense.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> pointed to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> as an area where unexpected political developments had created great uncertainty, and she urged <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to provide increased investment and support to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. Confidence in the future of that British colony, which reverts to Chinese rule in 1997, was shaken severely by <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s military assault on pro-democracy demonstrators in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in June and an ensuing crackdown on political dissent. `` It is absolutely vital we should do everything we can to keep up the confidence of the people in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>,'' she said. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, who arrived Tuesday in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> to attend a conference of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, a grouping of right-of-center political parties, called her visit `` timely.'' `` With so many changes taking place in the world, it is very important that the great democracies, and particularly the economic summit seven countries, should consult very closely with each other,'' she said. She said she hoped to create an `` unprecedented partnership'' with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in the 1990s and to resolve lingering trade problems.
