<HEAD>Dukakis Signs Law Requiring Judges to Explain Lenient Sentences</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Judges wo n't be able to let violent criminals off without prison unless they explain their sentences in writing under a new state law. Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who signed the legislation Wednesday along with a bill increasing aid to victims of violent crime, acknowledged the law would probably lead to more crowded prisons. But he said he is committed to expanding prison space. `` If a judge is not going to sentence someone to prison for a crime of violence, he should have very good reasons _ reasons that will hold up to public scrutiny,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` We're going to expect judges in this state to be accountable.'' Judges `` are fallible and make mistakes occasionally,'' he said, adding that that would be much less likely to happen under the new law because judges will be forced to think carefully about their rulings. Chief Justice <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Liacos </PERSON> said through a spokeswoman that he is n't against the concept but is worried it will require more work of judges without providing extra staff. The other bill signed by <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> at least doubles the fine imposed on criminals to help victims. A sponsor said the legislation would raise $ 5 million a year for services such as translation and counseling as well as $ 1.5 million toward direct compensation to victims.
