<FIRST>r a AM-HorseFerry     09-21 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Horse Ferry,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lake Stakes Claim to Only Remaining Horse Ferry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The only known horse ferry left in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> will be preserved at its underwater location in <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Champlain </LOCATION>, where divers will be allowed to examine it and take photographs. `` Just as we're protecting the natural beauty of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Champlain </LOCATION>, what today's event marks is the protecting of the historic resources,'' said <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Madeleine </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunin </PERSON>, who dedicated the wreck Wednesday along with state and local officials, historians and representatives of the diving community. The horse-powered ferry, which cruised 150 years ago, and three other shipwrecks are marked with surface buoys and underwater signs that encourage divers to look but keep the wreck intact. A bright yellow sign placed on the horse ferry advises divers to `` take nothing but photos.'' The horse ferry, or `` teamboat,'' was powered by two horses or mules who walked on a large turntable mounted beneath the deck. The turntable drove a pair of paddle wheels that allowed the ferry to travel the lake between <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state. The identity and date of the boat are still unknown, but it most likely cruised the lake in the first half of the 19th century. The design is based on an 1819 patent, and the <ORGANIZATION> Vermont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> granted the first teamboat charter on <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Champlain </LOCATION> in 1821. The last teamboat was retired around the time of the Civil War. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Crisman </PERSON>, a marine archaeologist who is documenting the wreck, said the two-horsepower boat would have been heard several miles away, `` with the horses' hooves clumping on the deck and the iron gears clanking.'' Today its remains are in 45 feet of water less than a mile northwest of the <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION> breakwater. It is 63 feet long and 23 feet wide, and is extremely fragile, said <PERSON> Giovanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Peebles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> state archaeologist. Divers can see the algae-covered wreck from five to 15 feet away. <PERSON> Crisman </PERSON> said the most spectacular part is the paddle wheels, with the iron hubs and oak spokes still complete, although badly deteriorated, rising 10 feet above the bottom.
</TEXT>
