<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> today won the support of former President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> for spending $ 9 million to aid the anti-Sandinista opposition in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s elections next year as a way to `` make the playing field level.'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, who as head of the <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freely </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elected </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heads </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> will lead an observer delegation to the Nicaraguan elections, said as long as the money is used in accordance with Nicaraguan law, it will benefit the political process. He spoke with reporters after meeting with the president. The Nicaraguan election law requires that half of any money coming into the political process from outside the country be given to the country's electoral council that runs the elections. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> reiterated his opinion that indications are the elections will be fair, although some in the administration remain wary of the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>' sincerity. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was expected to send a formal request for the aid to <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> as early as today, according to congressional sources. The aid is intended to help long shot opposition candidate <PERSON> Violeta </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON> get a fairer shot in the presidential election scheduled for February. Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> has been sounding out prospects for the measure with congressional leaders, and one <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> source who spoke on condition of anonymity said responses had been encouraging. Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, D-Conn., a critic of past administration efforts to aid opponents of the leftist <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> regime, said late Wednesday his initial reaction to the package was favorable The money _ to be funneled both directly to the opposition political coalition and indirectly through the quasi-governmental <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> election observers _ would meet an estimated 80 percent or more of <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON> election budget, according to administration estimates. The endowment is a private foundation created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1982 to support democratic elections worldwide, using money appropriated by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Proponents of the aid package said the administration believes it would lend credibility to the opposition and make it easier for <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON>'s coalition to raise additional money from other countries and individuals. It also would help level the playing field for the fledgling opposition coalition against the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION>, which has held power since a 1979 revolution. Administration officials and many in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> believe the elections, while an uphill battle for the opposition, offer the best opportunity in a decade to oust the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> and President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, who are closely linked to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Most of the aid, some $ 5 million, would go to NED for use in non-partisan efforts at voter registration, voter turnout and election organizing, said sources in both parties and both houses of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, all of whom spoke on condition of anonymity. The administration believes those efforts can be at least indirectly helpful to <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON>, the publisher of the opposition newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> and the candidate of the opposition coalition known as <ORGANIZATION> UNO </ORGANIZATION>. The move would require no change in NED's charter, which prohibits direct partisan political activities. Another $ 2 million would go directly to <ORGANIZATION> UNO </ORGANIZATION>, but under Nicaraguan law would have to be split 50-50 with the country's electoral commission, which will run the elections. The remaining $ 2 million would help fund the activities of election observer groups such as one to be sent by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, the sources said. In visits to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> last week, <ORGANIZATION> UNO </ORGANIZATION> representatives asked for overt <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid for `` the electoral process'' in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, despite what they said was the certainty that the Sandinistas would seek to use <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> support as a propaganda weapon against them. Earlier this month, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration had considered asking for $ 3 million for an open, direct donation to <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON>'s campaign, but modified that approach in the face of congressional opposition.
