<HEAD>Gunmen Kill Parliament Member; Syrian-Christian Clashes Kill One</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three men armed with AK-47 rifles opened fire Thursday on a Sunni Moslem member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, killing him and his driver and injuring two passers-by, police said. Across <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and surrounding mountains, Syrian forces and gunners loyal to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> leader, Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, dueled with mortars and tank cannons. Police said at least one person was killed and six wounded, raising the overall toll to 927 killed and 2,731 wounded since the latest round of fighting broke out March 8. The attack on <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> Nazim </PERSON> <PERSON> Kadri </PERSON> occurred as the 74-year-old politician entered his car outside his home in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> at about 10:20 a.m., according to witnesses. A police spokesman said <PERSON> Kadri </PERSON> and his police driver, Sgt. <PERSON> Sami </PERSON> <PERSON> Suleiman </PERSON>, were killed instantly and two pedestrians were injured, one seriously, in the shooting. One witness said the killers jumped out of a red car parked behind <PERSON> Kadri </PERSON>'s. `` The gunmen called <PERSON> Kadri </PERSON> by name, the deputy looked at them,'' the witness said, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` Two gunmen opened fire. <PERSON> Kadri </PERSON>'s driver drew his pistol, but another gunman took several shots at him from an automatic rifle before he managed to open fire.'' The witness said the killers sped away, shooting into the air. There was no immediate claim of responsibility. An official obituary released by <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>'s public relations department said <PERSON> Kadri </PERSON> was first elected as a representative for the central <LOCATION> Bekaa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> in the one-chamber house in 1951. The former lawyer was `` repeatedly elected'' until 1972 when the latest parliamentary elections were held. The civil war, which broke out in 1975, has prevented further elections. <PERSON> Kadri </PERSON>'s assassination brought to 73 the number of surviving deputies in the 99-seat Parliament. Twenty-five have died and the seat of former President <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON> became vacant when he was elected head of state in 1982. The latest violence occurred as an <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> committee tried to enforce a cease-fire call. Druse warlord <PERSON> Walid </PERSON> <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON> told the Kuwaiti newspaper Al-Qabas that the peace plan issued last week by the three-man committee was `` inadequate.'' He demanded guarantees that arms supplies to <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> would be cut off. <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON> said that without guarantees of a halt of weapons to <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, the plan would amount to no more than a `` mere truce.'' <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> receives weapons from <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, a bitter rival of <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> has 40,000 troops in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> under a 1976 mandate to quell the civil war. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> says <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> violated the mandate by siding with the Moslems in the civil war, and he has vowed to drive them out. The latest violence broke out after <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> in March imposed a blockade of ports run by Moslem militias. The Syrians responded by shelling the Christian enclave north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, home to about 1 million Christians.
