<HEAD>Texas School Bus Crash Kills 18, Injures 49</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf pvs, `Cox said ...' to CORRECT city to Carrollton.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MCA1, MCA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A school bus was hit from behind by a delivery truck and plunged into a watery gravel pit this morning, authorities said. At least 18 youngsters were reported killed and 49 other people injured. Divers pulled several bodies from the 12 feet of murky water covering the bus, which was carrying students to junior and senior high schools in Mission when it fell on its side into the 40 - to 45-foot hole, authorities said `` They were just trapped. We had to break the glass of the windows to get in,'' said <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Nye </PERSON>, a scuba diver who said he pulled seven bodies out. <PERSON> Nye </PERSON>, who was driving his children to school at the time of the accident, said, `` You could n't see at all in there.'' <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION>, said at least 18 people, ages 12 to 18, were killed in the 7:40 a.m. accident, which occurred in clear, dry weather near the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> border about 75 miles from <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION>. Rescuers used a crane to lift the bus from the water but divers continued searching at midday for any more victims. The number of people aboard the 70-seat bus was not immediately known. The bus driver and the truck driver were being treated at hospitals, authorities said. Their conditions were not known. The owner of the unfenced pit alongside the road was not immediately known. `` We're going crazy here,'' said firefighter <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortiz </PERSON>. The youngsters' parents `` are very hysterical. They have really lost control, some of them.'' <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> said it was the worst school bus accident in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> history. The two worst such accidents in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history occurred in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>. In 1988, 24 children and three adults on a church outing died in a fiery collision near <LOCATION> Carrollton </LOCATION>. In 1959, 27 people were killed when a bus went into a creek in <LOCATION> Prestonsburg </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrera </PERSON>, who was trailing the bus and the soft drink delivery truck, said the truck ran into the back of the bus, knocking it into the pit. <PERSON> Herrera </PERSON> said he jumped into the water and helped rescue three students. Witnesses said that immediately after the accident, students and the driver climbed onto the bus and screamed for help. At <LOCATION> Mission </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, 29 people were in stable condition, said <PERSON> Nora </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, a nursing supervisor. Seven were in good condition at <ORGANIZATION> HCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grande </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON>. Thirteen were taken in <ORGANIZATION> McAllen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, spokeswoman <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> said.
