<HEAD>With AM-Poland-Convent, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Identity cards of 130,000 prisoners of the <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> concentration camp, which once were stored in sealed Soviet archives, have been released and turned over to the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said Thursday. `` The deaths of over 74,000 people were neatly recorded, day after day, hour after hour, in 46 huge volumes,'' <PERSON> Valentina </PERSON> <PERSON> Fatyukhina </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> research department, told <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. `` Their names, the birth dates and the names of parents were written down,'' she said. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the information was given to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, which will soon begin the task of processing the cards, making it possible to identify the citizens of many countries who were victims of <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, was one of the most infamous concentration camps run by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> during World War II. An estimated 2.5 million Jews were killed at the camp during the war. Ms. <PERSON> Fatyukhina </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> material was found by Soviet soldiers at the end of the war and shipped to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said access to the volumes only became possible about a year and a half ago as more and more archives were opened to researchers under the policy of glasnost initiated by President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. `` Nobody expected that 130,000 individual cards of concentration camp inmates existed,'' <ORGA