<SECOND>PM-Day Care Tax,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Tax Law May End Under-the-Table Payments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEOFFREY HAYNES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new federal tax law aimed at collecting unreported day-care income may thin the ranks of baby sitters and drive up the cost of child care, tax specialists and industry spokesmen say. The law requires parents to provide the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> with the name and Social Security number of their day-care provider if they want to deduct the cost on their federal income taxes. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> will check the cost reported by parents with the amount reported by baby sitters as the agency goes after an estimated $ 7 billion in day-care income that goes unreported each year. `` I do n't know that they'll send a grandma to jail, but it will be tough on them,'' said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Barros </PERSON>, a tax preparer who specializes in day-care provider returns. The law applies only to day care provided while parents are at work. `` We will indeed be cross-referencing to see if that baby sitter claimed that as income,'' said <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Wreford </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. Day-care providers not claiming the payments as income on their tax returns could be required to pay back taxes with interest and a $ 50 fine, <PERSON> Wreford </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Barros </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Stockton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, says it may take the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> two or three years before it's equipped to double-check a large number of returns for day-care income. Baby sitters collecting money under the table may be more likely to raise their prices once they are required to declare the income, <PERSON> Barros </PERSON> said. The National Association for Family Day Care, a non-profit organization representing about 3,000 day-care providers, said it supports the new law. `` The association feels anything that can be done to provide a more professional setting for child care is beneficial,'' said <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollestelle </PERSON>, accreditation administrator. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> says parents who seek the deduction without providing the Social Security number or tax identification number of their day-care provider could be turned down for the credit. `` We may lose some providers,'' said <PERSON> Carole </PERSON> <PERSON> Quarterman </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coordinating </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Detroit-Wayne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` There are some people whose clear intention is to make some money on the side and not report the income.'' The credit allows parents and those paying for the care of mentally or physically incompetent dependents to deduct a certain percentage of their care costs directly from their income taxes. Those eligible usually can claim a credit ranging from 30 percent of the expense, if their income does not exceed $ 10,000, to 20 percent if their income exceeds $ 28,000.
