<HEAD>Cranston Critical of Bush Efforts in Pacific Rim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday that it remains committed to enhancing economic cooperation and dialogue with Asian Pacific nations, but that it will take time, effort and patience. But Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, D-Calif., criticized <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomacy in the area as `` complacent'' despite an economic boom in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> that's bringing unparalleled prosperity and trading opportunities and problems <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>, assistant secretary of State for East Asian and <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> Affairs, told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration believes it's essential to build a framework `` to help manage the increasingly interdependent economies of the <LOCATION> Asian-Pacific </LOCATION> region.'' Consultations, he said, are under way with nations along the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> rim `` to strengthen the consensus for an open trading and investment system essential for sustaining global economic growth into the 21st century.'' Consensus building is `` a delicate and measured process'' that is difficult to rush, <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> said. However, <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON> said `` there is insufficient initiative from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to prepare for the challenges of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> century.'' `` And key <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> powers appear too willing to trot out the same tired excuses to avoid the tough decisions necessary to organize for the challenge of the 21st century,'' said <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, chairman of the Foreign Relations subcommittee on <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. A Pacific Basin Forum, <PERSON>