<FIRST>r i AM-Saudi-Executions     09-21 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Saudi-Executions,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convicted Shiite Terrorists Beheaded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABDULLAH AL-SHEHRI</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sixteen Shiite Moslems from <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> were beheaded Thursday for exploding two bombs in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> at the height of the Moslem pilgrimage to the holy city, the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said. An <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> statement implicitly blamed <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> for the attacks, which killed a man and were believed connected to the centuries-old feud between Sunni and Shiite Moslems. Four other Kuwaitis were sentenced to 15 years and 20 years in prison and 1,000 to 1,500 whiplashes for the bomb blasts, the ministry statement said. Nine defendants were acquitted, it said. Convictions and sentences were decided and confirmed by lower and appellate courts of Islamic scholars, the statement said. A Pakistani man was killed and 16 other pilgrims of various nationalities were wounded when the bombs went off the night of July 10 as 2 million Moslems gathered for the culmination of the pilgrimage, or hajj. Thursday's report was the first official word that arrests had been made in connection with the blasts near the Grand Mosque in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, Islam's holiest shrine. The executions were carried out `` in accordance with Islamic law,'' the statement said without elaborating. Sources close to the government, who requested anonymity, said the Kuwaitis were blindfolded and beheaded by sword at dawn in a Mecca prison compound. Government sources said <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> refused a <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> request to extradite the bombers. Full confessions from the condemned men will be broadcast on television, the announcement said. It described the blasts as `` an evil crime ... an aggression on the sanctity of the holy sites and on the pilgrims ... -LRB- and -RRB- of the entire Moslem nation.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said the defendants plotted the attack at meetings in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> and the Saudi city of <PERSON> Medina </PERSON>. Their aim, it said, was to spread `` terror and fear in the hearts of the pilgrims ... and show that -LRB- <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> -RRB- was unable to protect the house of God.'' Every Moslem, Sunni or Shiite, has a duty to make the pilgrimage to <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, the birthplace of the 7th century prophet <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>, and to <PERSON> Medina </PERSON>, where <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> is buried. Sunnis and Shiites disagree about who should have succeeded <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which has an overwhelming majority of Shiites among its nearly 50 million people, had been urging Moslems to seize <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Medina </PERSON>. Without naming <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s statement said the July bombings were perpetrated `` at the instructions of the mischievous ones, who are enemies of this nation and for all pilgrims of God's house, and cooperating with those mischievous ones on such debauchery and terrorism in the most sacred spot in the world. Since the late <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s 1979 Islamic revolution in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, Iranian pilgrims have tried to turn the hajj into a political forum to spread his fundamentalist teachings. In 1987, Iranian pilgrims clashed with <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> security, leading to the deaths of 402 pilgrims, most Iranians. After that, <LOCATION> Riyadh </LOCATION> restricted the numbers of pilgrims. This drew protests from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which boycotted the 1988 and 1989 pilgrimages. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, citing subversion and terrorism, severed relations with <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> in April 1988.
