<FIRST>r w AM-WolfPayment     09-21 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wolf Payment,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wildlife Group Pays for Wolf Damage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A conservation group that has been pressing for expansion of wolf ranges said Thursday that it has agreed to pay two <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> ranchers for livestock believed lost to wolves. Defenders of Wildlife said it will pay $ 1,700 to the ranchers to compensate for the loss of a cow and seven calves. The group said it is paying full market price for the cow, which animal experts said was a definite wolf kill. Government officials said the calves were probably wolf kills, and the group paid the farmers 50 percent of their value. Defenders began offering compensation for stock lost to wolves three years ago. The only other claims under the program came in 1987 when it paid farmers $ 3,200 in compensation for 10 sheep and five cows. The program is part of the non-profit group's effort to encourage the reintroduction of wolves into the northern Rockies, including <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION>. Stockmen in that region have opposed restoration of wolves to the area, fearing losses to the animals. `` Those of us who would like to see wolves return to select locations in the northern <LOCATION> Rockies </LOCATION> are ready and willing to assume financial responsibility for such a program,'' said <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> of Defenders of Wildlife.
