<HEAD>Winery Asks Distributors to Pull Cheap Brands From Skid Row Areas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead to CLARIFY that Gallo asked distributors to pull
stock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> has asked distributors to pull Thunderbird and Night Train _ the drink of choice among derelicts _ from Skid Row liquor stores across the nation. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> E. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; J. Gallo Winery, ordered retailers in such areas Wednesday to halt sales of the high-alcohol, screw-top wines. The Skid Rows were not identified. At the same time, the company said, the wines should not be blamed for the problem of drinking among street people. Rather, retailers who sell the products to `` obvious alcoholic derelicts'' should be stopped by stricter enforcement of laws, the winery said. `` This practice has led to the assertion that these products cause Skid Row conditions and, therefore, that by stopping the sale of high-proof wine the problem of Skid Row can be solved,'' the company said. `` We believe this thinking is naive and that the use of these products on Skid Row is merely a symptom and not a cause.'' Thunderbird and Night Train are made with a hint of wine flavor and fortified with grape brandy to boost the percentage of alcohol to about 18 percent. The wines usually sell for 90 cents to $ 1.50 for a three-quarter liter bottle. <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> called the wines `` an affordable alternative to other alcoholic beverages'' and warned that alcoholics deprived of one source will simply find another. The company claims about 26 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wine market, with estimated sales of four million cases of the two wines each year. <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>, with about 20 commercial brands, is a privately held company with total sales of reportedly more than $ 1 billion annually.
