<HEAD>Hurricane-Damaged Puerto Rico Awaits Disaster Relief</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Storm-weary residents searched for scare water, gasoline and grocery items Thursday as crews worked to restore the island's water and elecricity, knocked out by Hurricane Hugo. Police said a 94-year-old woman, <PERSON> Emilia </PERSON> <PERSON> Negron </PERSON> <PERSON> Figueroa </PERSON>, was found dead Wednesday in her home in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>, raising to 26 the number of deaths blamed on Hurricane Hugo. The storm hit the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commonwealth Monday after passing through a string of <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> islands. Police said the woman apparently fell, was unable to get up and drowned when water rushed into her home. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Thursday declared <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> federal disaster areas, making them eligible for emergency relief funds. A team of 1,100 soldiers dispatched by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> entered the <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Croix </ORGANIZATION>, which was pummeled by <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> and then hit by a looting frenzy. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> said about 600 people had been evacuated from <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Croix </LOCATION>. It said crewmen on board the cutter Bear reported that the city of Fredericksted in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Croix </LOCATION> `` erupted'' at sunset Wednesday and that firing from automatic weapons and small arms could be heard. Adm. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Staff </ORGANIZATION>, described the situation as `` near anarchy'' and said troops had rifles and were ordered to shoot if necessary to defend themselves. But presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the situation had improved. `` The troops are having an obvious impact in controlling the looting and other lawlessness associated with the destruction. It is impossible to say at this point how long they will have to be there,'' he said. Gov. <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Colon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> said the government was taking an inventory of the damage and expected disaster relief money to be made available within two weeks. The Red Cross was sending thousands of cots and bedding for some of the island's estimated 25,000 people still in shelters. Coast Guard planes continued shuttling food, medicine, bedding and clothes to the 8,500 residents of the offshore islands of <LOCATION> Vieques </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Culebra </LOCATION>, which were devastated by the hurricane. Seventy percent of the island remained without water and 25 percent was without electricity. Health officials warned a possible health hazard if the island remained without water for much longer. <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruiz </PERSON> <PERSON> Javier </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Puerto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aqueduct </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sewer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, said five electric motors for water pumps arrived from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on Thursday to replace those demolished at <LOCATION> Carraizo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dam </LOCATION>, which provides water to much of the capital of 1.1 million people. He one of the five motors would be installed by Friday morning and would begin distributing water to the capital on a rationing basis. By Monday, the authority expected to have water service restored to 80 percent of the island, which has a population of 3.3 million. Many hospitals in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION> metropolitan area cut back services because of water shortages, and at least two, <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jorge </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, stopped admitting patients Wednesday. At <ORGANIZATION> Ashford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presbyterian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, personnel worked 36 hours straight to deliver babies and take care of the injured from the hurricane, said <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Millon </PERSON>, the hospital's executive director. `` Everybody's pitching in,'' he said. The hospital had its own water supply and generators, he said. Supermarkets were opened on shortened hours, but bottled water and canned foods were almost impossible to find. There was also shortages of baby food, disposal diapers and milk. `` Yesterday we sold all the water we have,'' said <PERSON> Pilar </PERSON> <PERSON> Colon </PERSON>, manager of a 7-Eleven. Looters stole the store's cigarettes and liquor after the hurricane broke its front windows. <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Colon </PERSON> said dairies back in operation after being shut down by power outages had agreed to donate 300,000 quarts of milk a day to the needy. Gasoline was also in short supply in some areas. A line of more than a dozen cars waited at one of the few service stations opened in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>.
