<HEAD>Hurricane Hugo State-By-State</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a state-by-state look at developments Thursday as hurricane Hugo closes in on the eastern coast of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FLORIDA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Low-lying and coastal areas near <LOCATION> Fernandina </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> on the northern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> coast next to <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> were under a voluntary evacuation. Predictions called for tropical-storm force winds and less than 5 inches of rain. Three nursing homes were evacuated in <LOCATION> Fernandina </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, and patients were moved out of <LOCATION> Nassau </LOCATION> <LOCATION> General </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Amelia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. Schools in <LOCATION> Nassau </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Duval </PERSON> counties were closed. Most busineses in <LOCATION> Fernandina </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> closed Thursday afternoon. Shelters were set up in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> but civil defense authorities did not plan evacuations. Surfers headed into the bigger than normal waves at <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>GEORGIA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> opened shelters and advised people to leave their homes. Gov. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> declared a state of emergency in <LOCATION> Bryan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Camden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chatham </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Glynn </PERSON>, Liberty and McIntosh counties. Thousands fled barrier islands and coastal areas. Bumper-to-bumper traffic stretched at least 30 miles inland from <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION>. Hotels and motels were booked to capacity in <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> and as far inland as <LOCATION> Statesboro </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hinesville </LOCATION>. Coastal school systems canceled class for the rest of the week. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said the storm was taking a gradual northward turn, with the eye headed toward <LOCATION> Myrtle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, indicating <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> would be spared the brunt of the storm. Authorities still expected flooding, but less damage. Officials at <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> planned to play their game Thursday night against <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SOUTH CAROLINA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> ordered a mandatory evacuation of coastal barrier islands and shorefront, and dispatched national guardsmen to assist. In <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> was boarded up, businesses were closed and classes at public schools and universities canceled. Hospitals in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> stockpiled supplies, discharging patients well enough to go home and moving others to hospitals inland. At one hospital, officials also prepared for an influx of maternity patients, since some studies indicate that low atmospheric pressure could advance labor.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>NORTH CAROLINA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Evacuations were ordered or recommended for six counties on <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s coast. Residents of barrier islands and low lying areas within a half mile of the Intracoastal Waterway were told to evacuate. A flood watch was in effect for the entire state and a tornado watch was issued for parts of central and eastern <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. Shelters were open and a curfew was declared from 7 p.m. until further notice at <LOCATION> Wrightsville </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>. Other evacuated areas were under 11 p.m. to 6 a.m. curfews. Residents bought tape, lamp oil, flashlights, bottled water and other necessities. Plywood sold briskly to be used in boarding windows and doors. Other hot items were flashlights, ice chests and batteries.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WASHINGTON, D.C.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> area could expect sustained winds of more than 70 mph and as much as 5 inches of rain. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> placed emergency equipment at many of its facilities.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MILITARY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Pope Air Force Base officials at <LOCATION> Fayetteville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, ordered 12 to 14 C-130 transport planes to <ORGANIZATION> Little </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> to wait out the storm. The remaining 10 or 11 C-130s at the base were moved to hangars. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> sent four ships from <LOCATION> Mayport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> up the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Johns </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> toward <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION> to prevent crowding at the docks for the remaining two aircraft carriers and 11 ships. At <ORGANIZATION> Jacksonville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION>, 45 P-3 Orions were to wait out the storm at <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> bases in <LOCATION> Abilene </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. About 60 helicopters on base were being moved into hangars.
