<HEAD>Grace Says Wasteful Nation Needs `Waste Czar'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Grace </PERSON>, who headed a presidential commission on government costs in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, called on President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> Thursday to name a `` waste czar'' to lead a campaign against waste of public money. `` We are in a crisis situation, and nothing less than a war on waste, with the full support of every taxpaying American, will stop <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' wasteful spending,'' <PERSON> Grace </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. `` To lead the war on waste, I am calling for the appointment of a waste czar, reporting directly to the president,'' he said. Grace, chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> W.R. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, was chairman of the President's Private Sector Survey on Cost Control, also known as the <ORGANIZATION> Grace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, from 1982 until the commission reported to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in 1984. He is now co-chairman, with syndicated columnist <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, of Citizens Against Government Waste. <PERSON> Grace </PERSON> said the `` waste czar'' should have authority cutting across governmental agencies, much like that of <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, appointed by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to coordinate the administration's war on drugs. Grace noted that the federal debt stood at $ 1.6 trillion when he last spoke to the press club in early 1984, shortly after his commission's report was presented. `` Now I'm back, five years later, and the federal debt stands at $ 2.9 trillion, or nearly double what it was in 1984,'' he said. He said the waste czar should be given a mandate to carry out the recommendations of his commission as well as cost-saving recommendations of the congressional <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> and government inspectors general. `` We do n't need more taxes. We need less spending. We need less waste. And that's why the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people need a waste czar to protect their interests,'' he said. <PERSON> Grace </PERSON> also announced appointment of <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keyes </PERSON>, who was assistant secretary of state for international organization affairs in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, as president of Citizens Against Government Waste.
