<FIRST>r w AM-EducationDemographics     09-21 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Education Demographics,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Schools, Social Service Agencies Should Coordinate Efforts: Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Children who are hungry, sick or homeless are poor learners, a study by a private educational group said Thursday, calling for greater coordination between schools and social service agencies. The <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said the study found that changing demographics and lifestyles of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> families have created problems that schools alone can not solve. Only 6 percent of families are the so-called traditional ones with a breadwinner father, housewife mother and two children in public schools, said the report. Forty percent of the nation's poor are children, 15 million children are being raised by a single parent and 2 million children live with neither parent. The study, entitled `` The Same Client: The Demographics of Education and Service Delivery Systems,'' said the average income for female-headed households with children is only $ 11,200. <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodgkinson </PERSON>, director of the group's Center for Demographic Policy and the author of the report, also pointed to limited transportation options for the poor _ such as having to travel by bus and subway to get to work, day care and school _ and the lack of low-income housing _ 8 million low-income renters competing for 4 million housing units _ as creating great hardships, particularly for working mothers. As for health care, <PERSON> Hodgkinson </PERSON>, a former director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, said 11 percent of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s school children are enrolled in special classes for the handicapped. Roughly one-third of these children, he said, would have a smaller handicap, or none at all, if adequate medical care had been provided during pregnancy and in infancy. `` It is painfully clear that a hungry, sick or homeless child is by definition a poor learner, yet schools usually have no linkage to health or housing organizations outside those run by the schools themselves,'' said the report. `` At a time when service organizations are increasingly strapped financially, this kind of interactive organization holds promise ... It may well be that with few increases in funding, we could still magnify the effectiveness of each dollar several times through programs based on interagency collaboration at each governmental level.'' <PERSON> Hodgkinson </PERSON> said that in recent years, there has been more dialogue among government agencies with the same function, but one outcome has been `` organization maintenance, not improved services.'' `` For the urgent problems we face, this is not enough. Service organizations must begin to see their interdependence across functional lines,'' he said.
</TEXT>
