<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands fled <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>'s barrier islands and parts of its coastline Thursday, but Hurricane Hugo's new northward path offered hope that the state would be spared its full force. `` I think we escaped the brunt,'' said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Stelle </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Glynn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> emergency operations spokesman, after the center of the storm was 200 miles east of <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> coast could expect winds of 40 to 50 mph, near tropical storm strength but far short of the fury closer to <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON>'s center. <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Diamond </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said flooding was expected, `` but hopefully we're looking at less damage.'' Earlier, <ORGANIZATION> GEMA </ORGANIZATION> opened shelters and advised about 142,000 people, more than 95,000 of them in <LOCATION> Chatham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, to leave their homes. By mid-afternoon, <LOCATION> Tybee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> on the north end of the coast and <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Simons </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> to the south were virtual ghost towns of boarded-up buildings. The only open business on <LOCATION> Tybee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> appeared to be <PERSON> Nickie </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Lounge </LOCATION>, where a handful of holdouts gathered. As he sipped a drink, 63-year-old island resident <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dowell </PERSON> scoffed at the idea of heading for <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION>. `` I do n't go in there even when the weather's good,'' he said. Authorities said they would cut 