<HEAD>GAO Report Sees Problems in Veterans' Housing Loan Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A veterans' housing loan program is having financial problems because of high foreclosures and may require more aid than the Veterans Affairs Department has requested, according to a government audit. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> audit covered the department's financial statements for 1987 and'88, but made special note of <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION>'s housing loan `` The primary cause of the loan guaranty fund's increased need for funding beyond that generated through normal operations was the weakened financial condition of certain sectors of the economy, particularly energy and agriculture,'' according to the report released this week. The loan guaranty fund guarantees a portion of private sector loans made to eligible veterans at special terms. About 13 million veterans have taken advantage of VA housing programs. The fund largely paid its ways through the 1970s, but its requirement for appropriations and money transfers `` has increased significantly since 1980.'' The fund required $ 900 million in transfers and appropriations in 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. Congress and the VA are making several efforts to address the issue, and <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> says the problem is lessening because of a decline in foreclosures. <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> had 44,693 home loan foreclosures in fiscal 1987 and 48,963 in fiscal 1988, the report said. Foreclosures totaled 38,721 in the first 10 months of this fiscal year, said <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON>. `` We expect further improvements ... and we expect the numbers to continue to decrease,'' she said. <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> says the fiscal year appropriation for the fund was $ 778 million, with $ 120 million of that in supplemental funds,. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report says <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> will need about $ 100 million in tranfers from the direct loan fund plus about $ 453 million in additional direct appropriations in fiscal 1990. The direct loan fund is a separate fund used for direct mortgage loans to severely disabled veterans. The report noted several possible influences that would change <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION>'s estimates: _ A higher foreclosure rate than <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION>'s projection _ The continued sale, without-recourse, of loans on properties aquired by VA through defaults When VA finances foreclosed property sales, it can package several loans for sale to an investor. The sale with recourse guarantees that <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> will make good on any future default. Without recourse means the investor can not go against VA. The without-recourse loans, though supposedly providing less liability, provide less cash at time of sale, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> says. A law will prevent VA from making without-recourse sales after Sept. 30, but <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> is proposing legislation to give it flexibility in determining which types of loans to sell. _ A `` significant lapse'' of <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION>'s authority to collect a 1 percent funding fee on loans. The last time there was such a lapse _ six weeks in 1988 _ <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 30 million, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said.
