<HEAD>House Democratic Leaders Try to Get Rank-and-File in Line on Taxes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Subs 19th graf pvs, Rep. William, to CORRECT Gray's leadership
title. ^By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 House Democratic leaders struggled Thursday to sell party members on a deficit-reduction plan whose key element is a multibillion-dollar tax increase for the nation's 600,000 richest taxpayers. But there was no rush by rank-and-file Democrats to embrace the proposal, aimed at staving off President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan to cut the tax on capital gains. The Democratic alternative has a capital-gains break of its own. `` This is an awful plan,'' Rep. <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorgan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.D. </LOCATION>, a member of the tax-writing <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said of the proposal. `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wants to give big tax breaks to the rich, and we want to give them to the near-rich.'' House Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, D-Wash., defended the plan, which includes tax-deductible Individual Retirement Accounts for all workers, as fair and sound `` There is very substantial positive reaction to this proposal,'' he said. Ways and Means Chairman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, D-Ill., who would be expected to manage the Democratic alternative in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, said after a closed meeting with party whips: `` There's not too much unity here. Also attending that meeting was <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, who recently cautioned party lawmakers against repeatedly calling for tax increases in the face of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s no-tax-increase pledge White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> complained that expanding IRAs `` amounts to a tax increase.'' `` If you institute a proposal that reduces revenue, the government deficit gets larger and leaves you with even more pressure for a tax increase,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. House Republican Whip <PERSON> Newt </PERSON> <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> told colleagues that he was `` absolutely amazed that liberal Democrats would rush into a tax-increase fight after the lessons of 1984 and 1988,'' when Democratic presidential candidates portrayed as favoring higher taxes were swamped. The Democrats' still-emerging plan is intended as a substitute for the capital-gains tax cut that Republicans and six maverick Democrats pushed through Ways and Means last week. The cut, which <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> endorsed, is part of the committee's deficit-reduction plan. Democratic leaders note estimates that 80 percent of the benefit of the capital-gains reduction would go to those with annual incomes over $ 200,000. After briefly accelerating revenues, they contend, it would deepen the budget deficit in 1992 and beyond. As an alternative, Democratic leaders proposed: _ Expanding IRAs so all workers, regardless of income, could have a deductible plan The money could be withdrawn without penalty to finance the down payment on a first home or for college education. _ Eliminating a quirk in the 1986 tax overhaul in a way that would raise taxes on the richest 600,000 couples and individuals The quirk requires some upper-middle-income Americans to pay a higher rate of tax on part of their earnings than applies to the wealthiest taxpayers. Under that law, for example, a single person with $ 75,000 taxable income pays a top rate of 33 percent on a $ 10,000 pay raise or investment windfall. But a $ 250,000-a-year earner pays only 28 percent tax on a similar increase in income. The Democratic plan would apply the 33 percent rate to all taxable income above $ 44,900 for a single person and to all above $ 74,850 for a couple. _ Assuring that the 33 percent rate would not apply to any capital-gains income Thus, the maximum tax on capital gains, which for some upper-middle-income people is 33 percent, would be cut to 28 percent. Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, D-Pa., who as <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Majority Whip is the Democrats' chief vote-counter, called the proposal `` a continuation of the simplification of the tax code'' that would encourage saving and investment Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON>, D-Kan., said the plan gives the party a chance to stand for something, rather than just oppose the capital-gains cut The capital-gains reduction has drawn little public response, he said, but `` the mere mention of IRAs caused the phone to ring.'' Rep. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., calling any capital-gains cut a blow against deficit reduction, said there would be `` a large group of us that will vote against any kind of change. `` I think it's a mistake for the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to be advocating an increase in taxes until the president has done that,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, D-Ga., chief sponsor of the capital-gains cut that won Ways and Means approval
