<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it halted enforcement against a polluting <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> waste-burning plant for more than two years because it did n't want to damage a criminal investigation of the facility. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> action frustrated area parents whose children had a higher-than-usual incidence of cancer, the House Government Operations environment subcommittee was told. The enforcement halt also stymied state officials, who aggressively sought civil penalties against the Marine Shale Processors plant, near <LOCATION> Morgan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> officials found air, water and hazardous waste violations at the plant. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reich </PERSON>, acting assistant <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator for enforcement, said the agency declined to take action under an agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which believed that any civil enforcement could lead to dismissal of criminal evidence and other problems. Subcommittee Chairman <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., said there's something `` fundamentally wrong'' with a system that `` allows violations for years to go unabated. `` It's unfair to the community'' to say that a pending criminal investigation means `` we can not protect the safety of people,'' he said. The criminal investigation ran from November 1986, when the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> searched the plant, to last July 24, when the company pleaded guilty to three pollution violations _ one felony and two misdemeanors _ and was fined $ 1 million. The violations involved hazardous waste storage, creating an obstacle to navigation and allowing contaminated storm water to enter a waterway. <PERSON> Reich </PERSON> said only an imminent health danger would have changed the policy, and it did n't find one. But Rep. <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. `` Billy'' <PERSON> Tauzin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>., who represents the district where the plant is located, said there is a higher than average rate of child cancer in the area and a state study has tried to determine if the Marine Shale plant is responsible He said there is no conclusive evidence to implicate the facility. <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Processors </ORGANIZATION> is located along <PERSON> Bayou </PERSON> <PERSON> Boeuf </PERSON>, part of the heavily traveled Gulf Intercoastal Waterway System. The facility burns hazardous waste, producing a byproduct known as aggregate, which is used as a substitute for gravel in road building. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Olde </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, an attorney representing the company, said in an interview `` There are no hazardous releases'' from the firm's operation He said the company was not responsible for child cancer in the area, saying he suspected `` chemical companies that have been dumping chemicals all around'' his region of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. `` We're not making hazardous waste. We're trying to clean up hazardous waste,'' he said. `` We make a clean product.'' State officials first discovered pollution violations beginning in August 1985 but were asked by the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to place enforcement on hold while the criminal investigation continued, according to <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Megginson </PERSON>, assistant secretary of legal affairs for the <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZ