<FIRST>u a AM-Day-CareSafety     09-21 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Day-Care Safety,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Day Care May Be Safer Than Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SARAH NORDGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Day-care centers may be safer than home for avoiding childhood injuries, a researcher said Thursday, suggesting that injury rates could be lower still with a little more attention to playground hazards. `` Parents have always had the bad news that kids in day-care are at increased risk of infectious disease,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Sacks </PERSON>, a medical epidemiologist at the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. `` Here's some good news for a change: they are probably at less risk of injury and death from injury than they are when they're not at day-care,'' he said. Sacks and his colleagues studied 143 injuries among 5,300 children at 71 <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> day-care centers between June 1987 and May 1988. Centers reported any injury that required medical or dental attention to the researchers, whose study is published in Friday's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> The researchers said that 3.54 percent of children in day-care could be expected to be injured at the center in a given year. They extrapolated from their data that, if children were to stay at day-care 24 hours a day, 365 days a year, 14 percent would incur an injury. `` A typical injury rate for children in a community in one year is about 35 percent,'' <PERSON> Sacks </PERSON> said. `` That suggests to us that children in child care are probably safer than when they are in the community at large.'' An earlier <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> study reported similar findings. The <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> researchers did not specifically study children injured at home, but cited previous research on their injury rates. Dr. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> pediatrician, said although he had n't seen the new study `` there is a certain amount of logic to it.'' `` In a well-supervised day-care center the environment has been looked at for hazards probably more than in the average home,'' said <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>, who edited a day-care manual for the American <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pediatrics </ORGANIZATION>. `` And many children who are at home do not get the amount of ongoing supervision as a child does in a day-care center,'' he said in a telephone interview. In the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> study, most injuries _ 58 percent _ were caused by falls and 68.5 percent were head injuries, the researchers said. Most injuries, 54 percent, occurred outside, with outside accidents accounting for 76 percent of the most serious injuries, the study said. The high number of playground injuries could be cut with a few simple measures, including the installation of impact-absorbing surfaces, such as wood chips or sand, Sacks suggested. Playgrounds should be examined regularly for possible hazards, such as equipment that is not stable, he said. `` As I drive by playgrounds, I often see staff congregated talking to each other while kids play,'' he said. `` When a kid is on a playground, it's time for heightened supervision, not less.''
