<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The foreign minister said Thursday he will meet with his British counterpart next week in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to discuss restoring diplomatic and commercial ties severed at the outbreak of the 1982 <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> war. It would be the first meeting between Argentine and <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> foreign ministers since the 74-day war in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>, which left dead nearly 1,000 people. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavallo </PERSON> said his meeting with Foreign Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Major </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> will take place Wednesday at <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cavallo </PERSON> will fly to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Saturday with President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>, who is scheduled to address the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. Argentine and British diplomats are scheduled to meet Oct. 17-18 in <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> to discuss renewing diplomatic and trade relations. Such a move would in effect set aside for now the dispute stemming from their rival claims of sovereignty over the Falklands. The islands off <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> have been ruled by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> since 1833. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> claims it inherited the territory, which it calls the <LOCATION> Malvinas </LOCATION>, when it declared independence from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> in 1810. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> invaded the islands, inhabited by about 1,800 people of <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> descent, on April 2, 1982. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> counterattacked and defeated <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION