<HEAD>Doubts About US Debt Plan Raised as IMF, World Bank Meet</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS new 15th-16th grafs: ``A Treasury,'' with Treasury reaction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New doubts were raised Thursday over prospects for the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's strategy to reduce the $ 1.3 trillion Third World debt burden as delegates from 152 nations began arriving for talks on global economic issues. Questions about world pollution, political upheavals in communist <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the roller coaster ride of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar were all expected to be addressed during the annual meetings of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. But the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> debt plan, unveiled last March by <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, was the major topic on the agenda because resources of the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> are crucial to the success of the effort. The administration found itself facing new questions about the <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> plan after three of the largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks this week decided to set aside more than $ 4 billion in reserves to cover losses related to Third World loans. <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it was setting aside $ 2 billion to cover loan losses. Earlier, <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the country's third largest bank, had said it was setting aside $ 1.15 billion and <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said it was boosting its loan loss reserves by $ 950 million The decisions will translate into big third-quarter losses for all three banks. The increase in loan loss reserves, which are expected to be followed by other banks, came after <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, the Third World's largest debtor with $ 110 billion in loans outstanding, missed making a $ 1.6 billion interest payment this week Banking analysts cited the <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> debt plan as another factor driving banks to boost loan reserves. Under the plan, banks are encouraged to forgive a portion of their loans to debtor countries in exchange for guarantees supplied by the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> that the remaining debt will be repaid. Thus, the <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> plan forces the banks to formally acknowledge that they will receive less than full repayment on their loans. Executives at both <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> cited this as one reason for boosting their loss reserves. Last week, final agreement on debt reduction terms was reached with <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, the first country to qualify for assistance under the <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> strategy. Some banking analysts said they feared that the actions by major banks to boost loan loss reserves could be a signal that these institutions would no longer lend new money to Third World countries. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Getman </PERSON>, an economist with the <ORGANIZATION> WEFA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, said that so far the only bank that is even considering making new loans to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Litan </PERSON>, an economist at the <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said the question of new money on the part of commercial banks was a concern and he said it pointed to the need for a commitment of much greater government resources to make the <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> plan work. `` The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration does n't want taxpayer bailouts for the banks and they seem to equate substantial <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> guarantees as the equivalent of a taxpayer bailout,'' he said. `` But I think you are going to need those kinds of guarantees on both old and new debt in order to move the program forward.'' A <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official praised the decisions to boost loan loss reserves as a `` further move to realism by these commercial banks that we welcome'' and denied that the actions represented a threat to continued lending to debtor nations. `` By strengthening their financial position, banks really have more flexibility to participate in a broader range of options, incluidng debt reduction or debt service reduction and new money,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. While both the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> are expected to spend substantial time discussing the <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> debt strategy, analysts said they expected little to be committed in the way of increased funding. <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> Managing Director <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Camdessus </PERSON> told reporters the Mexican debt package offered encouragement to other debtor nations to push forward with negotiations with their creditor banks. On the issue of assistance to <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Camdessus </PERSON> told reporters that <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> officials were holding discussions with officials of both countries aimed at providing assistance to support economic reforms in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The problems of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> were also expected to be taken up at the meetings. World Bank President <PERSON> Barber </PERSON> <PERSON> Conable </PERSON> told reporters Wednesday that he hoped to be able to resume lending to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> soon. Seven loans totaling nearly $ 800 million were suspended in June following the confrontation between Chinese troops and student protesters in <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>. Before the opening of the formal sessions of the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, finance officials of the world's seven richest countries were scheduled to hold talks all day Saturday to review global economic issues. The closed-door meeting, hosted by <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, will likely focus on efforts by the rich nations to stabilize the value of the dollar, which has been rising for most of this year, despite efforts by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its allies to drive it lower. The rising dollar threatens to derail the administration's effort to lower the huge <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. A stronger dollar makes <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods less competitive on overseas markets and invites higher imports.
