<HEAD>Woman on Life Support Dies When Electricity Disconnected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMMOND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman on life support died after a utility company disconnected power to her home instead of the house next door, a company spokesman said Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. President <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Neale </PERSON> said an employee was sent to disconnect a customer's service in this <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburb because the bill had not been paid However, the employee accidentally turned off the power to the sick woman's home. Service was disconnected about 10 a.m. Tuesday, and a relative notified the power company about a half hour later that power had been cut off and that life-support equipment was in use, <PERSON> Neale </PERSON> said. `` A customer service representative working with the relative immediately initiated a call to dispatch an employee to the home to restore service,'' <PERSON> Neale </PERSON> said. Service was restored by 11:10 a.m. The woman, described as in her late 50s or early 60s, was taken to <ORGANIZATION> Saint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Margaret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hammond </LOCATION>, where she died about 3 p.m. `` We have expressed our sincere regrets and condolences to the customer's family and offered any assistance we can provide,'' <PERSON> Neale </PERSON> said. He said the electric company would pay for any medical or funeral expenses. `` The accidental disconnection of service was a tragic mistake and we take responsibility for it,'' <PERSON> Neale </PERSON> said. The woman's name and medical condition were withheld at the family's request. The woman was not on the company's life support registry, which lists customers who use life support and medical treatment machines in their homes. People on the registry get priority service whenever there is a power outage. Their meters are tagged and service is never shut off, <PERSON> Neale </PERSON> said. `` Because we had no record of the customer's life support equipment, the electric meter was not tagged. Had it been tagged, it would not have been disconnected,'' <PERSON> Neale </PERSON> said.
