<FIRST>r w AM-Fighers-Jammer     09-21 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fighers-Jammer,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sen. Pryor Charges Jammer Flawed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s planned $ 4.8 billion system for jamming enemy radar is `` seriously flawed'' and production of the joint <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> program should be put on hold, a senator charged Thursday. `` I believe we have discovered a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> embarrassment and a potential waste of billions of dollars,'' said Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ark </LOCATION>. The Airborne Self-Protection <PERSON> Jammer </PERSON>, under development since 1969, is used to deceive or jam enemy radar and will be used on <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> fighters, including the F-14, F-18, F-16 and AV-8B. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> plans production of 2,369 jammers. To date, $ 577 million has been spent on research and development of the system. <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>, in a speech on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor, said unclassified <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> documents quote testers as saying the system is `` marginally operationally effective. In order to become potentially effective, ASPJ effectiveness must be improved for all threats not meeting reference criteria.'' The senator complained that further testing on the system is not planned until 1991 when more than 300 systems will have been produced, or committed to production, at $ 2 million a copy. `` All arrows point to a multibillion dollar rip-off,'' <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> said. In a letter to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Comptroller General <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowsher </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> asked that the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, review the testing, costs and possible alternatives to the jammer system. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> declined comment on the charges until it has seen <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>'s comments.
