<HEAD>Quayle at Conservative Meeting in Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> joined conservative party leaders from around the world Thursday at a meeting expected to focus on ways to help drives toward greater democracy in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> came to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> from a two-day trip to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, where he toured the Demilitarized Zone and denounced communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> as an `` astonishing dictatorial regime.'' He shares the spotlight at the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, who asked the West to give stronger support to reforms initiated by Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. British officials said Prime Minister <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> and <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> had a half-hour meeting and discussed East-West relations and <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, where Vietnamese troops began final withdrawal moves on Thursday. On Saturday, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> will visit <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> with his wife, <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON>. Next week, he holds talks with Prime Minister <PERSON> Toshiki </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON> and other Japanese leaders before traveling to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, founded in 1983, groups 26 right-of-center political parties, and holds leaders' meetings every two years. Representatives from 17 nations are attending this meeting, with <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON>, head of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s long-governing, conservative <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, acting as host. The three-day conference ends Saturday. Comments by <ORGANIZATION> IDU </ORGANIZATION> officials and advance texts of speeches indicated a major theme would be moves toward greater democracy in such East bloc countries as <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. A senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration official said that in <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s keynote speech at a luncheon Friday, the vice president will urge his fellow conservatives to help democratic forces in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, as well as in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> `` In Central and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the crunch is really coming now,'' said the official, briefing reporters on condition of anonymity. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Peacock </PERSON>, leader of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s opposition <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said in a speech prepared for delivery Friday that <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> `` is today at a watershed in its history -LRB- and -RRB- many states in the <LOCATION> Asia-Pacific </LOCATION> region are also searching for a new strategy.'' `` Who would have thought when we established the <ORGANIZATION> IDU </ORGANIZATION> in 1983 that we would, six years on, be witnessing such changes. We must renew ourselves in the battle of ideas and lead the agenda.'' <PERSON> Peacock </PERSON>, who is to become <ORGANIZATION> IDU </ORGANIZATION> chairman, said the organization should `` examine ways in which we can give practical assistance to those sympathetic parties that are developing in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>.'' The outgoing chairman, Norwegian former Prime Minister <PERSON> Kaare </PERSON> <PERSON> Willoch </PERSON>, told a news conference European conservatives have been traveling in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to make contacts with pro-democracy activists. `` I think this is very important, because through such contacts it is possible to help those groups fighting and working for freedom in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` This is a very complicated issue, because we all want to help, and we know that some sorts of help may be counterproductive. So thorough study of what's going on and what can be done are very useful.'' <PERSON> Willoch </PERSON> said it was premature to think of having Eastern European groups join the <ORGANIZATION> IDU </ORGANIZATION>, since forming non-communist political parties was still difficult. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> flies to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Friday to meet with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. She had lunch Thursday with Emperor <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON>. In comments to reporters, she praised <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> as `` the most bold and courageous leader the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has had while it's been under communism. What Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is attempting to do ... is in the interests of liberty as a whole and in the interest of all other nations who believe in the cause of democracy as well. `` We should do, therefore, everything we can to support this great, historic movement.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> noted a trend in favor of Western political and economic views but cautioned against relaxing defenses. She predicted a period of `` very great uncertainty'' in East-West relations and cited unexpected developments in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> as a strong example.
