<HEAD>Bush Presents Medals to Young Heroes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Thursday presented medals for bravery to a 12-year-old girl who rescued a Japanese tourist from the ocean in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> and an 18-year-old boy who subdued a gunman at his <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> high school. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in a White House ceremony, also presented a Young Americans Medal for Bravery posthumously to a 17-year-old who died rescuing victims of a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> bus accident. <PERSON> Angela </PERSON> <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Campanoli </PERSON>, a seventh grader from <LOCATION> Lacey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, a former student at <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gabriel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Alhambra </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, received the medals. <PERSON> Angela </PERSON> was vacationing with her family at <LOCATION> Maui </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, in October when she dove into the surf and helped pull out a Japanese woman being swept away by a strong current. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> subdued a student armed with an assault rifle who was holding 70 students hostage at his high school April 26, 1988. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> praised them for `` facing death and challenging eternity.'' The president also presented a posthumous award to <PERSON> John </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rosie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bankston </PERSON>, parents of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> <PERSON> Bankston </PERSON>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> drowned July 17, 1987, while helping rescue others when a church bus and a van carrying 43 people from a children's camp were swept into the <LOCATION> Guadalupe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Kerr </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. `` We know that a parent's grief is a special hardship,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told the couple. `` But we hope that your grief is tempered now by pride _ a pride in your hero, your son, <PERSON> John </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also presented Young American Service Awards to: _ <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Donovan </PERSON>, 18, of <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, for a variety of community activities, including leading a Boy Scout troop with disabled members and for leadership in a student group campaigning against drunken driving _ <PERSON> Freddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Torres </PERSON>, 19, of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, for volunteer work in helping keep young people away from drugs and for his work in AIDS prevention programs _ <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, 20, of <LOCATION> Ethel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, for starting a food bank for the needy _ <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Urich </PERSON>, 19, of <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, for leading efforts to clean up beaches along the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> coast `` These services may not be as dramatic as pulling someone from the surf or subduing a gunman, but <PERSON> Freddy </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> and <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON> know something very profound: that it is in the daily accumulation of small acts of kindness that can be improved; and often, that lives can be saved,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said.
