<HEAD>Grand Jury Indicts Federal Drug Agent, Wife</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with detail from indictments, comments from
Ms. Terry, her lawyer; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A grand jury has indicted a federal drug agent, his wife and the owner of a construction company on charges of conspiracy, tax evasion and laundering large amounts of cash, officials said Thursday. The federal indictment named <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> agent <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Harker </PERSON>; his wife, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON>; and <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Terry </PERSON>, who owns <ORGANIZATION> SKT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> was one of five recipients of the `` women of enterprise award'' sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Small </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> last year, said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Kutmus </PERSON>, her lawyer. She's a business partner of <PERSON> Roxanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Conlin </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney and Democratic gubernatorial candidate. <PERSON> Kutmus </PERSON> said she is a widow with two young children whose husband died in a construction accident. He called her `` a spokeswoman for women in non-traditional positions.'' `` I was shocked and outraged to learn that I was being indicted,'' Ms. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> said at a brief news conference. The 11-count indictment alleges that between 1986 and 1988 <PERSON> Harker </PERSON> and his wife `` spent, invested and profited by cash transactions exceeding $ 1 million.'' <PERSON> Kutmus </PERSON> said he had advised Ms. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> not to comment on the facts of the case, but `` the charges themselves are ruinous to her and her business.'' <PERSON> Kutmus </PERSON> said he would enter an innocent plea at arraignments scheduled for Oct. 2. `` She feels she is wholly innocent and that the charges are very ridiculous,'' <PERSON> Kutmus </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Harker </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> were charged with using a business they established `` to launder substantial amounts of currency which <PERSON> Harker </PERSON> had acquired and to funnel the cash through what would appear to be legitimate business transactions and loans between the two partners.'' The indictment also says <PERSON> Harker </PERSON> loaned thousands of dollars in cash to other drug agents and spent more than $ 30,000 in cash to buy rare coins. There was no mention of drugs in the indictment, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Beck </PERSON> refused to elaborate on it. <PERSON> Harker </PERSON>, 42, is a supervisory agent for the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> who joined the agency in 1971, and previously was assigned to <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Laredo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, before coming to live in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>. He could face 40 years in prison and $ 2 million in fines if convicted on all the charges. The Harkers also could owe taxes and penalties. Mrs. <PERSON> Harker </PERSON>, 40, faces up to 20 years in prison and $ 1 million in fines if convicted. Ms. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON>, 38, faces up to 30 years in jail and fines of up to $ 1.5 million. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office said in a statement released Thursday that the indictment was handed up Wednesday. It resulted from an investigation that began in spring 1988 `` as a result of information received by the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>,'' the statement said. In the indictment, <PERSON> Harker </PERSON> was charged with one count of conspiracy, three counts of tax evasion and four counts of using an interstate facility to promote illegal activity _ presumably the mailing of bundles of cash. His wife faces a conspiracy count and three tax evasion charges. Ms. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> faces three counts of arranging bank deposits to avoid a federal law that requires banks to report cash deposits larger than $ 10,000. The indictment details real estate transactions _ many in cash _ in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and other locations. Farmland, resort properties and homes were bought, the indictment said. The Harkers filed returns for 1986 claiming taxable income of $ 38,999, but it actually was more than $ 416,000, the indictment charged. For 1987, the couple claimed just over $ 34,000 but it really was nearly $ 680,000, the indictment charged. There was no mention of the source of the income in the indictment or accompanying statement.
