<SECOND>AM-Hersh Libel Trial,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hersh Testifies at Own Libel Trial: I Tried to `Follow the Truth'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Journalist <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON> <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON> testified Thursday he was trying to `` follow the truth'' when he wrote a book being challenged by a former <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> prime minister in a $ 100-million libel suit. <PERSON> Morarji </PERSON> <PERSON> Desai </PERSON>, prime minister from 1977-79, claims <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON> defamed him by saying he was a paid <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> informant and a valuable `` asset'' to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government during the administrations of <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON>, called to the stand by lawyers for <PERSON> Desai </PERSON>, testified he had made several errors in the first printing of `` The Price of Power,'' a book he wrote in 1983 about former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON>. The mistakes _ that <PERSON> Desai </PERSON> did not remain a cabinet member after he resigned in 1969 but was a member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, the spelling of <PERSON> Desai </PERSON>'s first name, and the year <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> returned to power _ were corrected in a second edition published a few months later. The mistakes are not at issue in the libel case. `` I made a mistake,'' <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON> testified. `` The Indian ambassador called me up, told me I had a mistake there.'' When questioned by the plaintiff's attorney <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Baumgart </PERSON> about his accuracy in reporting and writing, <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON> said he was attempting to be truthful. `` The notion is truth. I follow the truth, is what I'm trying to do,'' he said. <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON> testified that six sources told him <PERSON> Desai </PERSON> worked as an informant for the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>, but acknowledged that he said in two 1983 interviews there were only two. He testified that one source among the six told him <PERSON> Desai </PERSON> was paid $ 20,000 to be an informant. `` Did it occur to you this source may not be accurate,'' questioned plaintiff's attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Meara </PERSON>. `` Yes, it would to anybody,'' <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON> answered. But subsequent research `` butressed my view about certain important facts ... and increased my confidence which, in fact, was already high,'' <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON> testified. Under questioning, <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON> declined to reveal the name of another source who was a foreign service officer in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, for the Indian government. He said he submitted part of his manuscript prior to publication to the source for verification of its accuracy. Earlier, plaintiff's attorney <PERSON> Cyriac </PERSON> <PERSON> Kappil </PERSON> told the court <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> had been subpoenaed to testify, but his whereabouts were not known. `` We'll make every effort to bring him in,'' <PERSON> Kappil </PERSON> said. `` On a personal level, we prefer not to inconvenience Mr. <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> because of his schedule.'' <PERSON> Kappil </PERSON> said he would give <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> the opportunity to come in voluntarily before asking the judge to enforce the subpoena. He also said he was considering using a videotaped deposition made by <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> if he was unsuccessful in procuring the former secretary of state. Under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> libel law, <PERSON> Desai </PERSON>'s attorneys must convince the six-member jury that <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON> knowingly printed false, negligent or malicious material. <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON> won the Pulitzer Prize for international reporting in 1970 for his articles exposing the My <PERSON> Lai </PERSON> massacre in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> when he was a reporter for the