<HEAD>Seat Cushions Sub As Life Preservers In USAir Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-USAir Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lacking life jackets and vests, flight attendants had to throw seat cushions to passengers evacuated into <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> after a <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> jetliner broke apart in an aborted takeoff, a spokeswoman for the flight attendants union said Thursday. <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeast </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Attendants </ORGANIZATION> said the aircraft's cabin crew was unable to open all exits as the floor buckled and the plane broke apart. Seat cushions on commercial aircraft are designed to float, with enough buoyancy to support a person. Some flight attendants have been critical of rules that require inflatable life vests only on flights that spend appreciable time over major bodies of water, Ms. <PERSON> Yeast </PERSON> said. As it became apparent the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737-400 carrying 61 people would not stop safely, the attendants began yelling `` brace'' commands to get passengers to grab their ankles and put their heads down to reduce injuries, she said. `` The floor of the plane buckled up and down like a roller coaster,'' Ms. <PERSON> Yeast </PERSON> said, based on information the union received from flight attendants and others. Some passengers were sent down an inflatable slide into the water. Others scrambled onto the aircraft's wing. Passengers in the water hung on to floating timbers and other debris untio rescued. Later, Ms. <PERSON> Yeast </PERSON> said, flight attendants and the plane's captain tried to use the slide as a raft _ as slides are designed to be used in a pinch _ to reach several passengers caught in the rear of the cabin as the plane sections filled with water. But the slide deflated, apparently punctured by debris, she said. The interior of the plane was dark and shifting in the current, Ms. <PERSON> Yeast </PERSON> said, as at least one passenger yelled for help from behind a place where the floor had buckled all the way up to the ceiling. That passenger and others were rescued, but two other passengers died in the accident. Ms. <PERSON> Yeast </PERSON> said the pilot and last flight attendants stayed in the aircraft trying to free passengers and left only after rescue workers arrived and ordered them to evacuate. `` When the flight attendants realized passengers were going into the water, they ripped of seat bottom cushions and began throwing them out the door,'' she said. People were in the water for as long as 30 minutes, she said, and some started singing as they awaited rescue. Ms. Yeast identified the flight attendants on the flight as <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jolynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Galmish </PERSON>, <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrelson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> <PERSON> Donovan </PERSON>, all based in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>.
