<HEAD>FBI Won't Appeal Court Order in Discrimination Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 14th graf, bgng: The suit xxx to CLARIFY that Perez was
FBI's second-highest ranking Hispanic agent.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it will not appeal a sweeping court order that sets in place mechanisms to end what a judge found was systematic discrimination against Hispanic agents. The decision against appealing the May 5 decision by a federal judge in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> was made by Solicitor General <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Starr </PERSON>, the bureau said. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> made the announcement after receiving word of <PERSON> Starr </PERSON>'s decision. <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sessions </PERSON> said in a statement that after weighing `` the myriad legal, operational and institutional considerations,'' he recommended to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> that no appeal be pursued in the case. Sessions said the decision not to pursue the appeal is in the best interests of <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> employees. `` We must move beyond the frictions caused by this case to address the many vital challenges facing the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> in the 1990s.'' The court order in the class-action suit by 311 of the bureau's approximately 400 Hispanic agents directed the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> to adopt changes to end the `` unsystematic, excessively subjective'' method of promoting special agents In his order, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Lucius </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunton </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Midland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, stripped the special agents in charge of <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> field offices of the power to override decisions of career promotion boards. That system, the judge said, was `` anathema to nearly every reform advanced by the bureau and ordered by this court to improve the fairness and reviewability'' of promotion decisions. <PERSON> Bunton </PERSON> also appointed an outside panel of three attorneys to conduct a case-by-case review to determine if as many as 200 Hispanic agents should be promoted to compensate for past discrimination. Under the terms of the order, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> can appeal the panel's findings to the judge <PERSON> Bunton </PERSON>'s order came as a result of more than two years of litigation in the class-action case, in which he had earlier found discrimination against Hispanics in promotions and working conditions. The judge had found that Hispanic agents were often relegated to undesirable assignments, such as monitoring the wiretaps of Spanish-speaking suspects in a criminal investigation. Since taking office in November 1987, Sessions conducted a review of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s personnel and recruitment practices. He reorganized the bureau's equal employment opportunity office, going outside the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> to recruit a manager of that unit who now reports directly to him. In his order, <PERSON> Bunton </PERSON> acknowledged that the changes ordered by Sessions `` demonstrate energetic and good-faith effort to correct the disparities found by this court.'' The suit was filed in early 1987 by <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON> `` Mat'' <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s No. 2 agent in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>, the bureau's second-highest ranking Hispanic agent after he had suffered a series of demotions. The judge ordered <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> promoted to a job with responsibilities `` commensurate with his experience and training'' but denied any monetary damages or back pay to him or the other plaintiffs who eventually joined the lawsuit. As a result of the court order, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> was promoted to deputy assistant director of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s laboratory division in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s decision not to appeal was praised by Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, D-Calif., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on civil rights `` That's exactly the right decision, something we've been urging for many months,'' <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said. `` It's time for them to move on and get at the root causes of the problems associated with <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON>,'' the congressman said, referring to a racial harassment suit by a black <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON>. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> called the <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON> case `` a thorn in their side day after day.'' <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON> accuses the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> of tolerating racial harassment by white agents of him and his family while he was assigned to the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> field office. The lawsuit also accuses <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> supervisors of retaliating against him for complaining of racial harassment. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kairys </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON>'s lawyer, contended in a telephone interview this week that the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has filed a series of `` frivolous motions'' that he said were `` calculated to immobilize the court'' overseeing the case.
