<HEAD>Pay Up or Lose Your Vote, United Nations Tells Three Nations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said Thursday the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Equatorial </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION> are so far behind in their dues they risk losing their vote in the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Charter says any nation two years behind loses the right to vote in the Assembly. The Assembly may let the country vote if it is satisfied that failure to pay is due to circumstances beyond the country's control. The <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, which is assessed about $ 224,000 annually, must come up with $ 223,600 to keep its voting rights, said the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief's letter. <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, assessed more than $ 74,000 annually, must pay $ 12,057 and <LOCATION> Equatorial </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION>, assessed the same, must pay $ 46,300 to keep their votes. When a small, impoverished nation has been unable to pay in the past, its former colonial power or a major ally quietly paid the dues. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is also in arrears, but has refused to pay since the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> suspended its voting rights in 1974 as punishment for its racial segregation policy. If its voting privileges were restored, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> would have to pay more than $ 35 million to regain its vote. Dues are based on a formula that largely relies on a nation's gross national product The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> still owes more than anyone. As of Aug. 31, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> was $ 278.8 million in arrears for past years and owes more than $ 216 million for this year's dues, bringing the total close to $ 500 million. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is assessed for one-fourth of the regular <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> budget, about $ 216 million a year. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s administration began withholding a large portion of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dues starting in 1985 to spur reforms and budget cuts at the world body. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> announced a year ago he was satisfied with <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> progress along these lines and authorized full payment of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dues and payment of all back dues on a six-year plan. Congressional committees refused to pay back dues this year, citing constraints imposed by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> federal budget deficit.
