<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1434EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv22   09-21 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 22,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release PMs Friday, Sept. 22</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tax Logic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of the most intimidating threats to peace of mind is a <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> searching for new sources of revenue, because somewhere, somehow, someone will have to pay. The threat is all the more real because in this, if not in other matters, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' mind seems to be made up _ never on details, perhaps, but on the general idea that government forever will need more money. In ways most people do not understand, proposals for tax cuts become tax increases, and whenever a tax decrease escapes into law it is thereafter stripped of all its benefits, leaving little more money in taxpayers' pockets. Throughout the 1980s, tax cuts have been eroded by subsequent increases, some of them imposed with little publicity. Why? Because they appeared almost insignificant at the time. But as they say, little increases do add up. Consider the Economic Recovery Tax Act of 1981. It promised corporate tax reductions averaging $ 51 billion in the years 1987-89. But by 1986, says the <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, this `` reduction'' became a $ 20 billion-a-year increase. Somehow, such things happen when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> goes rummaging through the tax code, and it may happen again. As your neighbors might tell you, it is one of the most fearsome things that can happen to good Americans. The latest tax go-round probably was initiated by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who proposed that capital gains taxes, the kind imposed on investment earnings, be cut substantially, from as high as 33 percent to as low as 15 percent. To do so, he said, would raise revenue, for a couple of years at least, because lower taxes would encourage people who owned stocks to redeem them for cash, and thereby declaring their capital gains and paying their taxes. Besides, he suggested, it was only fair. Such investments involve risk, he observed. The benefits from such investments are delayed rather than immediate. And much of the tax is imposed on inflated rather than real returns. Some members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> rebelled, saying such a cut would be a gift to the rich, and could not be permitted. The rich should be taxed more, they said, and so they proposed a tax increase, which <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is now considering. In such manner has a tax cut generated the threat of a tax increase. Seldom, however, is any tax matter as open, clear and understandable as that. In the past, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has actually passed taxes it never meant to pass, and has ommitted items it thought it had included. Always there are surprises. In the recent tax increase proposal, for instance, the emphasis is on making life more expensive for the rich, even though the definition of `` rich'' is highly suspect. -LRB- In tax logic, for instance, a person who never made $ 20,000 a year but who, through lifelong discipline, may be rich for the one year in which the funds are redeemed, is defined as rich. And so taxed. -RRB- Somehow, in this latest proposal, the matter of private pension funds was introduced. They have lots of money, $ 2 trillion or more, so it was n't askew of tax reasoning to go after them. And so the suggestion is being made: Why not tax these tax-exempt entities every time they are involved in a short-term securities trade? Typically, the rationale being offered is not that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> wants more money, but that those pension funds should be investing for the long term. Too much of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, it is said, is thinking short-term. This will help correct it. It could do more than that. It could become the foot in the door, or if you prefer, the nose of the camel in the tent. That is, more could follow, drawn irresistibly by the vast possibilities of such vast sums of money.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End advance for PMs Friday, Sept. 22.</NOTE>
