<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 24, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Farmers Union, Yeutter Look at Farm Bill Differently</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> would agree that profitable, family-owned agriculture is a noble dream of American farmers. But the <ORGANIZATION> NFU </ORGANIZATION> has its own ideas how best to achieve mastery of the agricultural dream machine, and <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> has a few of his own. They're not alone. Many other agricultural and commodity organizations, individuals, analysts and special interest groups of all sorts are jockeying for position as <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> works on the 1990 farm bill to replace the 1985 law. And <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> is not the only one who has a say in what the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration wants in the 1990 bill. Trade policy, budget requirements, White House political nit-picking and dozens of other factors litter the road ahead. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> has said repeatedly that the administration does n't have its specific farm bill proposals ready for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> but hopes to outline those by the end of the year. But a look at some of <ORGANIZATION> NFU </ORGANIZATION>'s legislative desires and a few of <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>'s ruminations might help a bit to clarify some of the thinking as farm bill debate unfolds. Earlier this month, about 150 <ORGANIZATION> NFU </ORGANIZATION> members from 16 states, mainly in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, participated in a two-day `` fly-in'' to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that included brisk lobbying treks to <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. The current farm law, the Food Security Act of 1985, covers a multitude of programs, from conservation, credit and fish farming to food stamps, rural development, research and trade. But the heart of the 1985 law _ and its predecessors for more than half a century _ is the array of commodity programs that provide federal price supports and related benefits for milk, sugar, wool and major crops such as wheat, feed grains, cotton, rice and soybeans. Among other things, the 1985 law gave the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> more discretionary authority in administering commodity programs, including reductions in some of the price support benefits. A goal, supported heartily by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, was to help make <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> products more competitive in foreign trade. Supporters of this approach say the 1985 law has been successful in this regard. The <ORGANIZATION> NFU </ORGANIZATION> disagrees. `` Low farm prices are not the answer to our problems,'' says <ORGANIZATION> NFU </ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> <PERSON> Swenson </PERSON>. `` Low prices are the problem.'' In letters to members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Swenson </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> NFU </ORGANIZATION> vice president <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> said farmers and consumers alike `` are all interested in promoting the sustainability of our natural resources, promoting the sustainability of our communities and ensuring a stable, safe food supply.'' The <ORGANIZATION> NFU </ORGANIZATION> is proposing a 10-point legislative list that features `` a voluntary supply management program'' based on using bushels or other units of production instead of acres to control crop output. It also would encourage participation in the program by offering farmers higher price support loan rates and higher target prices for base levels of crop production. These are key items that the 1985 farm law allowed to be reduced. The <ORGANIZATION> NFU </ORGANIZATION> says a bushel-based system of supply management would allow the government to `` better predict farm program costs and give farmers income protection without sacrificing crop rotation flexibility.'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> also thinks there should be more flexibility for farmers to rotate crops and have more management control. `` A primary objective for the price and income support elements of the new farm bill should be to reduce the rigidity of present programs,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soybean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in July. One proposal, called the `` triple base'' plan, would limit crop deficiency payments under the target price formula _ a subsidy making up the difference between the market price and the target price for a specific crop _ to the existing base acreage or a portion of it. Farmers could then plant other crops on the remainder without losing any of their acreage base. `` Flexibility is not just a back-door way to cut target prices, as some have labeled it,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said. `` Even though budget constraints must be addressed in all 1990 legislative proposals, greater flexibility should and can be achieved because it is the right thing to do.'' The <ORGANIZATION> NFU </ORGANIZATION> wants <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to include in the 1990 farm bill a statement `` that would reaffirm policy designed to foster and sustain the family farm system of agriculture.'' It also would recognize that the objective `` is to ensure that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumers have ample quantitites of domestically produced, nutritious, safe and reasonably priced food and farm products. Such an objective is long-term and non-negotiable.'' One of the paragraphs, according to <ORGANIZATION> NFU </ORGANIZATION>, should declare that the 1990 farm bill `` must enhance, promote and be fully supportive of the family farm structure'' and `` must avoid measures which would be detrimental to family-scale operations.'' At a White House news conference on Sept. 15, <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> was asked about his role and the usual perception of farmers that the secretary of agriculture is their champion. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said he intends to be `` a champion for the interests of American agriculture'' and believes that he can be as vigorous and effective as anyone who has ever held the job. `` But I'm not always the champion for some of the programs that some ... would prefer to be enacted into law,'' he said. `` The question is what does one champion? And I'm going to be the champion of agricultural programs that I believe are in the best interest, the best long-term interest of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> agriculture.''
</TEXT>
