<HEAD>$Adv 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sun Sept 24 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Springtime Revisited for Foreign Policy Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's not quite a replay although it comes close _ President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is accused of timidly yielding the diplomatic initiative to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> but insists he is n't going to be pressured into hasty offers on arms control. When that script was written, only last May, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> produced the ending, silencing his critics with a proposal for conventional arms cuts in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> that upped the Soviet ante. Now the complaints are about foot-dragging on strategic arms reductions. There's no hint that the administration has a September surprise ready to match its springtime comeback. But the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> does control the agenda, and that carries with it the power to undercut <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> attacks on Bush-style diplomacy. It happened before, less than four months ago, with the same cast and similar dialogue. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> got the last word and Democratic leaders had to switch overnight from complaints to applause. In both cases, Soviet officials also criticized the administration's diplomatic pace. This time, 10 days before his Thursday meeting with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said the administration had been restrained, indecisive and timid in arms talks. The White House called that complaint mystifying. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democratic Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> said Monday that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` must reach beyond the status quo thinking that appears to dominate administration policy.'' `` He must cast aside the ambivalence, the hesitation and the timidity and adopt a more energetic and engaged policy toward the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and eastern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. `` The administration appears to have become complacent about the arms control process, trusting that the Soviets will do the work and provide the results.'' Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> dismissed <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>'s comments as political talk `` When the president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is rocking along with a 70 percent approval rating on his handling of foreign policy, and I were the leader of the opposition party, I might have something similar to say,'' he said. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and Shevardnardze are spending the weekend in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hole </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyo. </LOCATION>, discussing arms control and other U.S.-Soviet issues. `` Now, will we conclude a treaty in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>? The answer to that is obviously no,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` I think if you will judge us at the end of the day, hopefully next Sunday, that you will agree that we've moved the process forward substantially across the full range of our arms control agenda.'' He said that includes strategic arms reductions, chemical weapons, and long-stalled negotiations on nuclear testing. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said he also hopes the Soviets will move toward acceptance of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal that both sides cut their conventional forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> That was the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal that stilled the earlier round of criticism, after months during which the Soviets seemed to be out-maneuvering the new administration. Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> announced unilateral cuts in troops and weapons in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, scoring public relations points in western <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> while <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was silent, awaiting a review of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy. At home, the Democrats complained about the president's pace. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> turned that around at the end of May, proposing conventional arms cuts with solid allied support at the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> summit in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>. He said the offer put the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on the offense and tested Soviet intent. `` We may be at an important turning point in history, one in which the security environment in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> can be transformed,'' Sen. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said at the time. Now the cycle is recurring, with a new agenda. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said anyone who thinks the administration is reluctant to move forward on strategic arms talks is misreading his intent, perhaps because the conventional arms proposal was his first priority. `` We're working inside our own administration to have proposals that I think will capture the imagination of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Monday. He did n't say when. `` I think we have to be careful not to become frantic and rush out here to negotiate a treaty on strategic arms, or anything else for that matter, that would be non-ratifiable,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. The president said he was in no rush to stage a summit meeting with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. And he's calling the plays.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mears </PERSON>, vice president and columnist for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, has reported on <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and national politics for more than 25 years.
