<HEAD>Hotels Offer Free Lodging For Cancer Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI NOLTE BROWN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ethel </PERSON> <PERSON> Flippen </PERSON> was diagnosed with cancer in January, but a daily 160-mile round trip from her home to a hospital was daunting, and so was the cost of a hotel for the week of radiation treatments. <PERSON> Flippen </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Emporia </LOCATION>, was n't the only one faced with the dilemma. `` We were having patients call us from out of town saying they needed transportation into <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> for their radiation therapy and we were finding that these people were coming from long distances on a daily basis,'' said <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Rawls </PERSON> of the local <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. `` Financially it was hard on them ... physically it was hard on them.'' The society turned to the <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Richmond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Motel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which began offering patients free room and board. About a dozen, including <PERSON> Flippen </PERSON>, have taken advantage of the offer since the program began in March. `` I've had one patient tell me that she would not have been able to get her radiation therapy had it not been for the hotel lodging program,'' said <PERSON> Rawls </PERSON>. `` This is true of most of these patients. They could not afford to stay in a hotel Monday through Friday for eight weeks.'' <PERSON> Flippen </PERSON>, who underwent 25 radiation treatments at <ORGANIZATION> Massey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clinic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospitals </ORGANIZATION>, has stayed at four of the two dozen participating inns. `` If it had n't been for the hotels and motels, I guess I would have just died,'' she said. `` To see them come together on something like this ... to do something good for the community in a very competitive industry is something very special,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poppell </PERSON>, executive director of the society's state chapter. `` We've talked to a lot of our counterparts across the country, and we know of no other program where it's being made available at no cost to patients.'' Each of the participating hotels agree to provide two weeks of complimentary lodging a year. Referrals come from social workers, hospitals and oncologists such as Dr. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Goplerud </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. `` The typical patient will have treatments of four or five weeks. They often feel tired and may suffer a loss of appetite, diarrhea and nauseau,'' he said. `` The reason they require a place to stay is because many of them live a long distance from <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> and have to come in every day for treatment. They get tired out from the long drive.'' If free lodging were n't available, <PERSON> Goplerud </PERSON> said, hospitalization or missing treatments would be the only options for some patients. `` Some would continue to commute back and forth and feel miserable.'' <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> area hotel rooms range from $ 40 to $ 90 a night, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON>, executive vice president for the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Richmond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Motel associations, which are helping other groups set up similar programs. `` It's going to be a natural for these other organizations to pick up on this. For us this made sense,'' he said. `` It was a very positive thing to do.''
</TEXT>
