<HEAD>Food Allergies Implicated in Dizziness, Hearing Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Allergic reactions to foods may be responsible for dizziness, hearing loss and ringing in the ears among thousands of people who suffer a disorder called Meniere's disease, a study concludes. The study of 49 patients with the inner-ear disorder was conducted by Dr. <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Derebery </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. The institute's president is Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> House </PERSON>, former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s ear doctor The 49 underwent testing to determine their food allergies, then those foods were removed from their diets. Vertigo either was reduced or eliminated in 66 percent of the patients. Half experienced a decrease in ringing in their ears and several had dramatic improvements in hearing. The foods most commonly linked to <PERSON> Meniere </PERSON>'s disease were wheat, eggs, milk, corn, yeast and soybeans. Thousands of Americans have the disease, in which excess fluid accumulates in the labyrinth, the part of the inner ear that controls balance.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Scientists Fight Popcorn Lovers' Plague: Unpopped Kernels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Food engineering students cooked up 800 pounds of popcorn in an effort to combat the tooth-jarring plague that afflicts popcorn lovers everywhere: UPKs, also known as unpopped kernels. `` There are two basic problems that appear to cause an increase in UPKs and a decrease in popping volume: shelling of the kernel off the cob, and the moisture content of individual kernels at the time of popping,'' said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Eckhoff </PERSON>, a food engineer at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Urbana-Champaign </ORGANIZATION>. During the summer, food engineering students using a movie theater popper found that unpopped kernels were most likely those that were too moist or too dry. Large kernels at the butt of an ear of corn have the highest moisture content; small kernels near the tip have the lowest. `` It follows, then, that companies could process kernels of uniform size to decrease the number of unpopped kernels,'' the university said. The researchers also found that if a kernel's outside covering is damaged when kernels are removed from the cob, steam ca n't build up inside the kernel. That also creates those dreaded UPKs. `` We're looking at ways to precondition the corn to loosen the attachment of the kernel to the cob so you would n't need as much mechanical force,'' <PERSON> Eckhoff </PERSON> said. `` Then you would n't damage the kernels so much.'' The research was funded by <PERSON> Beatrice </PERSON> @ <ORGANIZATION> Hunt-Wesson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION>, parent company of popcorn maker <PERSON> Orville </PERSON> <PERSON> Redenbacher </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 25</NOTE>
