<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Salary increases for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> workers will average 5.3 percent this year, indicating that spending power probably will lag behind inflation for the second straight year, according to a new survey. The survey of 1,260 businesses found that, after taxes, raises will not match the increased prices of goods and services bought by urban wage earners and clerical workers, which rose at an annualized rate of 5.1 percent through August. The survey was released Wednesday by the compensation consulting firm <ORGANIZATION> Hewitt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
