<HEAD>Trade Ministry Plans Tax Incentives to Boost Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade ministry is considering tax incentives for companies that boost imports as a way to correct its $ 52 billion trade surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, officials said. `` We realize that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> accounts for half of the total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit and therefore we are trying to vigorously increase our imports,'' <PERSON> Yuzuru </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatakeyama </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters Wednesday. <PERSON> Hatakeyama </PERSON>, director general of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, said the ministry is considering a plan to grant special tax incentives for importers. During <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s industrial buildup after its defeat in World War II, incentives granted to exporters allowed them to reduce their taxes by from 1 percent to 3 percent of the value of their exports. The system was discontinued in 1964. <PERSON> Hatakeyama </PERSON> said the government is considering a similar system to promote imports. The tax breaks would not extend to importers of raw materials, he said. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is under pressure from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to increase its imports and institute other economic and trade policy changes to cut its surplus. Earlier this month, the two countries began a yearlong round of bimonthly talks on structural impediments to trade in each nation, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have said they expect `` measurable'' improvement in the trade imbalance by next spring. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> also has been named, along with <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, as a possible target of retaliation under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade laws for policies that allegedly hinder the sale here of supercomputers, lumber products and satellites. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Commerce Secretary <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON>, in a three-day visit to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> last week, welcomed the idea of tax incentives to Japanese importers as a far-reaching method of increasing imports and cutting the trade imbalance. Total Japanese imports have risen 16.5 percent in the first eight months of this year, and imports from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have increased by 19.9 percent from the same period last year, the trade ministry says. The senior trade official said the proposed tax breaks are not likely to be implemented until next spring at the earliest, since <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> would have to approve legislation. But <PERSON> Hatakeyama </PERSON> admitted the tax breaks could take even longer because of political uncertainties. Plagued by a series of scandals and an unpopular new sales tax, the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> lost its majority in the upper house of Parliament in July for the first time in 34 years. A general election for the more powerful lower house must be held by next summer. It is not clear whether the proposed tax incentives would be legal under rules of the international trade body known as the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. `` But we hope no countries would complain about this scheme,'' <PERSON> Hatakeyama </PERSON> said.
