<ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION>. Some analysts have speculated that <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> is interested in <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION>'s heavy truck business, an area where <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> is weak in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s heritage in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> dates back to the early years of this century. Company founder <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> started the automaker's European connection in 1903 by exporting cars to <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Five years later, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> opened an office in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, the company's first overseas branch. The continent has been important to <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> not only as a car and truck market but as a base for its earnings. During the past two years, profits from <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s European operations have risen, to $ 1.46 billion last year, while <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> American earnings have fallen. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, which has a number of European assembly plants, is n't the only <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automaker moving to increase its presence in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> before 1992. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lutz </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the vehicle-making arm of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday that the No. 3 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automaker has developed a network of 770 dealers in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The company recently introduced U.S-made versions of the <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spirit </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acclaim </ORGANIZATION> to the 