<HEAD>Major Airlines Ponder American's Proposed Fare Hike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's major airlines are pondering whether they should match an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> proposal that would raise some discount fares by more than 15 percent and double cancellation penalties. The increases proposed by American, one of the largest carriers, would take effect Sept. 29. They would follow a recent rise in a type of discount fare popular with business travelers, reflecting an effort by airlines to partly recoup revenue lost from bargain fares offered this summer to fall vacationers. Spokesmen for competitors of Dallas-based American said Wednesday those airlines were considering matching the increases but had n't decided `` I think there are several carriers out there that are inclined to match,'' said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Starkman </PERSON>, an airline analyst at the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Under American's proposal, the popular `` MaxSaver'' cut-rate fare often used by vacationers, which must be purchased 14 days in advance, would be increased by $ 10 to $ 20 per round trip. A `` MaxSaver'' ticket on American between <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, for example, would go from $ 338 to $ 358 round trip. The `` MaxSaver'' tickets would remain non-refundable. In addition, American would raise fares on seven-day-advance tickets by $ 30 to $ 60 round trip. The same <PERSON> Dallas-Los </PERSON> <PERSON> Angeles </PERSON> round trip ticket bought seven days in advance would go from $ 378 to $ 438. The penalty for changing or canceling a reservation would double to 50 percent of the ticket price. `` We're trying to get the yields up,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hotard </PERSON>, a spokesman for American. An airline's yield, which reflects the average revenue from passengers for each mile flown, is the lifeblood of the competitive air transport industry. <PERSON> Starkman </PERSON>, like many industry analysts, is expecting little improvement in yields overall for the rest of the year and into 1990. In mid-August, the airlines announced steep fare cuts for the fall, extending summer travel bargains. They slashed round-trip fares by as much as $ 160 to lure passengers in the historically weak autumn season. Most fares to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> were reduced by $ 100 into next spring. Last week, in an effort to recover some of the losses, the airlines boosted `` Supercoach'' one-way fares by about $ 20 for a one-way ticket. These fares are favored by business fliers because they have more lenient advance-purchase requirements than cheaper discount fares and do n't require a Saturday-night stay. Spokesmen for <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday those airlines were studying American's proposal but had n't decided if they will match it. If they do n't follow suit, it would be difficult for American to raise the fares alone and remain competitive. But <PERSON> Hotard </PERSON> said the airline planned to go ahead next week, in any case. American also announced Wednesday an increase in service from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> to become a larger competitor in that market, historically dominated by <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, which has been hobbled by a prolonged strike. American's efforts to buy <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s Latin American route network recently collapsed when <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> decided not to sell it. But American officials said the airline would seek government approval for routes on its own.
