<HEAD>Bush Rejects Colombian Plea on Coffee Quotas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has rejected a plea by Colombian President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> for a 1-year reinstatement of a coffee-export quota system that had been beneficial to Colombian farmers, the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> said. Colombian coffee prices have fallen sharply since the 74-nation <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agreement </ORGANIZATION> _ to which both the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> belonged _ collapsed in July after the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> pulled out in a dispute over prices with coffee-producing nations. <PERSON> Barco </PERSON>, whose nation relies on coffee as a major source of export earnings, had appealed to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to reconsider the coffee decision and to support reinstating the quotas for at least one year. But the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday that the decision would stand. <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s coffee earnings have slumped at the same time that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is seeking Barco's help in cracking down on cocaine exports. Colombian officials have suggested they will have an even harder time persuading hard-pressed Colombian farmers to grow coffee instead of coca if coffee export prices continue to slip. The agreement set quotas for member nations' exports aimed at suporting prices of beans at $ 1.20 per pound or more. Some Central American nations and others, supported by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, wanted larger quotas. After suspension of the quotas in early July, prices fell quickly to about 85 cents a pound. <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> has said this will cost $ 500 million a year in export revenue. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Barco </ORGANIZATION>, said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was ready to negotiate for a new quota system but was unwilling to adhere to the now-defunct agreement, presidential press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s letter was one `` expressing appreciation of the importance of coffee to the economies of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and other developing countries.'' The letter, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> continued, `` expressed his -LRB- <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s -RRB- disappointment that the members of the <ORGANIZATION> ICA </ORGANIZATION> were unable to settle ... two fundamental problems.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wanted an increase in export quotas for higher-quality coffees enjoyed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumers, and tough penalties against countries secretly selling coffee surpluses to Eastern bloc nations at prices below those charged the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> expresses his confidence that a lasting solution which is acceptable to other major members and respects market trends can be found,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s letter may have opened the way for negotiations on restoring coffee export quotas, a Colombian representative said. While <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> rejected <PERSON> Barco </PERSON>'s plea, he also said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was prepared to resume discussions on quotas at any time. Possibilities for restoring the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>'s export quota system may be explored next week at a week-long session of the 74-member group. `` The aim will be to maintain the momentum towards an economic agreement for coffee that brings back export quotas,'' <PERSON> Nestor </PERSON> <PERSON> Osorio </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s permanent coffee organization delegate, said in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. `` The council will look at the market situation and could set a timetable for negotiations,'' he added. Coffee prices have dropped by more than 30 percent since the <ORGANIZATION> ICO </ORGANIZATION> export quota system was suspended on July 4, and prices touched a 14-year low of less than 67 cents per pound last month. Allowing for inflation, coffee is now at its lowest level since the 1920s.
