<HEAD>Report Shows Shifts in Regional Growth Trends</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Economy Bjt and PM-Regional Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> retailers have fared better than their <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> rivals this year and sales at chain stores in oil-patch states have grown faster than elsewhere in the country, according to a new report. Department stores and discounters in the <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, metropolitan area posted the best sales gain for the first half of 1989 while <ORGANIZATION> Akron </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> retailers suffered the worst decline. These were among the findings in a regional retail sales report based on results from 6,000 stores, with at least 25 employees each, in the 125 largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> metropolitan areas. The stores account for $ 110 billion in annual sales. The retailers, which regularly submit sales figures to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, include such national chains as <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> K </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> mart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> J.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, mass merchants and department stores Using data collected by the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shopping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> is compiling a new monthly report that complements other government retail sales publications. The premier issue, released Wednesday, covered sales for June and the first 6 months of 1989. <PERSON> Ike </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagnado </PERSON>, director of research for the shopping center trade group, said the report indicates a region's health because consumer spending at general merchandise stores is a key element of economic activity. Nationwide, consumer spending accounts for about two-thirds of economic activity. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Loeb </PERSON>, a retail industry analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said at a news conference that the new reports will help analysts determine store traffic trends and sales momentum, which are crucial factors in assessing a retailer's prospects. According to the report for January through June, the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> or `` oil patch'' area of the country, including parts of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, had a sales gain of 11.2 percent for the first half from the corresponding 1988 period. The increase was by far the best of any region and compared with a national median increase of 4.5 percent. `` Since the oil-dominated economies have suffered through an extended widespread economic contraction, a recent turnaround has apparently been sufficient to usher in a wave of consumer spending,'' the report read. The West had a 6.3 percent sales gain in the first half of 1989. On the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, the south <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> states showed a growth rate of only 1.3 percent and the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> states trailed all other divisions within geographic regions, with a 2.6 percent drop in sales. In the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, the report said department store sales rose 4.3 percent in the first six months of the year from a year earlier but accelerated in the second quarter, posting a rise of 5.3 percent. Among specific metropolitan areas <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION> had a sales rise of 18.7 percent in the first half of 1989 to lead gainers, while <ORGANIZATION> Akron </ORGANIZATION> sales fell by 8 percent to lead the decliners.
