<HEAD>Former Heileman Chief Discouraged by Company's Troubles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The former head of <ORGANIZATION> G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heileman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> says he is discouraged by the company's troubles since it was acquired by Australian <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bond </PERSON>, but he declined to speculate whether the country's fifth-largest brewer might be sold again. `` It's unfortunate,'' <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Cleary </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Crosse </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON> is based. `` I certainly hope they get their act straightened out for the sake of the employees.'' <PERSON> Cleary </PERSON> said he would not speculate on whether <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON> might be sold. A spokesman for <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON> referred calls to <PERSON> Bond </PERSON>'s headquarters in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, but officials there could not be reached for comment. `` It's a tough business and he has an enormous amount of debt,'' <PERSON> Cleary </PERSON> said. `` We did n't have that debt.'' Through a series of acquisitions, <PERSON> Cleary </PERSON> built <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON> into a national power before it was bought by <PERSON> Bond </PERSON> in 1987 for about $ 1.3 billion. But the purchase of <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON> has contributed to <PERSON> Bond </PERSON>'s mounting debts, which reportedly exceed $ 4 billion. On Tuesday, <PERSON> Bond </PERSON> announced he was selling half of his brewery empire to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Lion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nathan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, for more than $ 760 million Under the transaction, <PERSON> Lion </PERSON> <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> will buy a 50 percent interest in and management of <ORGANIZATION> Bond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s Swan, Tooheys and <ORGANIZATION> Castlemaine </ORGANIZATION> breweries in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, and the group's hotel and associated liquor interests. <PERSON> Bond </PERSON> said in a statement that the brewery deal was `` another positive step in the restructuring and strategic refocusing'' of his group. He said it would create a `` formidable brewing alliance'' in the region, aimed at the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> as well as <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Under the proposal, the brewing assets will be folded into a new joint venture company, <ORGANIZATION> Australian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Breweries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pty </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, equally owned by <ORGANIZATION> Bond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Lion </PERSON> <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON>. Bond deferred for 12 months any decision to part with <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON>. Analysts say, however, <PERSON> Bond </PERSON> is bound to lose money whether he sells <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON> or decides to keep it. `` Heileman today is to some extent painted in a corner,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON>, a professor of marketing management at <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. `` The question is whether you operate it and bleed a little or take a big hit and move on,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Collopy </PERSON>, an industry analyst and chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Cleary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gull </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reiland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McDevitt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Collopy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. While the overall beer market has stagnated, <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON>'s share has eroded, falling from a high of 9.4 percent in 1983 to a current level of about 7 percent. Industry observers say <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON> was worth far below $ 1.3 billion when it was sold, and <PERSON> Bond </PERSON> would have a hard time finding a buyer. `` You're not getting anyone to pay $ 1.3 billion for the breweries,'' said <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinman </PERSON>, associate publisher of Beer Marketer's Insights, an industry newsletter. Analysts point out that <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON>'s sales started to slip before the company was sold, but <PERSON> Cleary </PERSON> was able to keep the company efficient and profitable. `` His helmsmanship helped hold it together better than anyone could,'' <PERSON> Collopy </PERSON> said. `` When you lose that, the underlying softness got exaggerated.''
