<HEAD>Pan Am Fined for Flight 103 Violations, But No Link to Bombing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS date to Dec. 21 in graf 2, `The Federal ...' This also
moved on general news wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> is being fined $ 630,000 for alleged security breaches mainly involving its flight that blew up over <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, but federal aviation officials say the violations did not lead to the bombing. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> announced the fines involving the Dec. 21 flight on Wednesday, giving the airline 30 days to pay or appeal. The action came as the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>, prompted by the Pan Am bombing and another apparent airliner bombing over <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> on Tuesday, passed a bill to bolster international aviation security. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> fine covers charges of improper screening of passengers and cargo boarding Flight 103 at <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> airports, as well as five other European flights within a few days after the bombing. The agency said its letter announcing the fines to <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> `` contained no allegations that any of the violations contributed to the Flight 103 tragedy.'' All 259 people aboard the flight were killed, as well as 11 on the ground in <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said all of the problems cited in the accusations have been corrected. <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Plaskett </PERSON> called the alleged security lapses `` administrative rather than substantive'' and also said they did not contribute to the bombing. `` There is no evidence that any of the items noted in the ... inspection by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> were in any way related to the bombing of our aircraft last December,'' said <PERSON> Plaskett </PERSON>. Investigators are still trying to determine who planted plastic explosives in a radio-cassette player found in debris from the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747's cargo hold. The fines came as a team of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investigators was setting out for <LOCATION> Niger </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to look into the crash of a DC-10 en route from <LOCATION> N'Djamena </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. The French airline <ORGANIZATION> UTA </ORGANIZATION> said a bomb apparently downed its plane carrying 170 people. A spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 victims' relatives, <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ammerman </PERSON>, reacted to the fines by saying the government, not airlines, should be responsible for aviation security. The relatives have called for a federal investigation into the bombing. Sen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Exon </PERSON>, D-Neb., praised the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> action, saying the fines would `` serve notice not only on <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> but all other airlines that we are going to be insistent on not only proper maintenance of the aircraft but proper screening of passengers and baggage that goes on airplanes today. The House on Wednesday passed a bill that would have the government pay $ 270 million for modern weapons-detection equipment at many <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and foreign airports. The <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has ordered airliners to install and pay for the devices. The legislation, approved 392-31, also would require for the first time that commuter airlines screen passengers and luggage, require airlines to acknowledge that they have received <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> warnings of possible security threats, and urge agreements with other countries to require detectable chemicals in plastic explosives. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> accused <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> of failing to properly check 31 passengers at <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> airport and another five at <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, where the flight to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> originated. Other violations were cited in the handling of passengers or cargo for three other flights from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and two from <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> within three days after the bombing of the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> jumbo jet. In some cases in which passengers were identified for further checks, hand-held metal detectors were used on their carry-on luggage rather than having it opened for physical inspection as required, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> said in May that all passengers and cargo boarding Flight 103 were thoroughly inspected. The airline said the allegations of security lapses `` appear to be based on a misunderstanding of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>'s procedures.'' A <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> lawyer who handles aviation cases, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Stengel </PERSON>, said that despite the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s failure to connect the lapses with the bombing, the fine might still be used by plaintiffs as evidence in support of suits against <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>. He said it could support allegations that <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> was not meeting all of its security responsibilities at the time of the incident. Another aviation lawyer, <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerrard </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, said he thought the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> fines would be excluded as prejudicial evidence in liability cases since the government has not concluded that the violations contributed to the bombing.
