<UNK>Congressional Panel Demands Lilly Documents</UNK>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A congressional subcommittee investigating the generic drug industry has asked <ORGANIZATION> Eli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to hand over several documents within two weeks. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mich </LOCATION>., sent a letter Tuesday to <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> in which he said an inspection report by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> made public last week `` confirmed that callous and cavalier business practices were commonplace in your <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> plant. <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> chairs the subcommittee on oversight and investigations of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, which has been investigating production problems and illegal payments in the generic drug industry and the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s approval process for generic drugs. Generic drugs are copies of brand name products that have lost their patent protection. The subcommittee's request seeks from <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> copies of documents dating back to Jan. 1, 1985, and covering <PERSON> Lilly </PERSON> responses to any inspections of its manufacturing operations; communication to or from the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> regarding inspections of manufacturing or research facilities for drugs produced or sold in this country; and a list of management personnel at the <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> plant. A spokesman for <PERSON> Lilly </PERSON> said the company had not received the letter. The 90-page <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> inspection report addressing <PERSON> Lilly </PERSON>'s tablet and capsule manufacturing facility criticized the company's quality control, manufacturing and record-keeping procedures. In response, <PERSON> Lilly </PERSON> recalled 18 lots of 10 products, temporarily halted all shipments from the <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> plant, and formed an in-house task force to revamp procedures to meet <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> objections. Last week <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>'s subcommittee asked the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> for the reports of all <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> manufacturing plant inspections worldwide since Jan. 1, 1985.
