<HEAD>Report: Texas Air Negotiating Sale of Reservation System</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf to UPDATE with no comments from companies; uppicks
4th graf pvs: Analysts estimated ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is discussing the sale of its computer reservation system to a <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> unit in a deal that could bring the troubled airline concern as much as $ 400 million, according to a report published today. Unidentified sources cited in the Wall Street Journal confirmed that negotiations with <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> were advanced and that barring a snag, an agreement could be forged within several weeks. A spokesman at <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> was said to be unavailable for immediate comment on the Journal report while in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> EDS </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Still </PERSON> said the company does not comment on speculation. Analysts estimated that <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s System One, the third-ranked computer reservation system in the airline industry, could fetch between $ 300 million and $ 400 million. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> has given no indication of what it might do with the proceeds from any sale. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> is facing considerable difficulties. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, its chairman, last month said he may sell an interest in <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s main operating unit. And its <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> unit is in bankruptcy proceedings. The Journal noted that the airline industry's computer reservation system is undergoing its own restructuring. Earlier this week, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> disclosed it was discussing merging its reservation system with PARS, an operation jointly owned by <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. And <ORGANIZATION> AMR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s Sabre reservation system has been seeking a partner after the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> quashed its plans to link up with <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>'s system. The paper also noted that a System One-EDS combination would mark the first non-airline owner of a computer reservation system. System One has a market share of about 19 percent, according to the Journal, roughly half that of <ORGANIZATION> AMR </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Sabre </ORGANIZATION> system. In addition to the work it performs for <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>, EDS is involved in health insurance, government and financial institution data processing.
