<HEAD>Crop Futures Gain on Frost Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Forecasts for freezing temperatures this weekend in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> gave grain and soybean futures a boost in early trading today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Some forecasters expect frost in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> Saturday night, with the cold moving into the eastern Corn Belt Sunday night. If frost occurs, it would be about a week ahead of normal. Analysts said the greatest threat would be to soybeans in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, where crops were planted late due to heavy spring rains. In the western Corn Belt, where the crops are more mature, `` I do n't think you're talking about yield losses, I think you're talking about quality problems,'' said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustafson </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION> Frost could slow the natural drying of mature corn and lock some chlorophyll into not-quite-ripe soybeans, causing some discoloration, <PERSON> Gustafson </PERSON> said. In early trading, wheat futures were \ cent lower to -LCB- cent higher with the contract for delivery in December at $ 3.91 -LCB- a bushel; corn futures were -LCB- cent to 1 cent higher with December at $ 2.29 -LCB- a bushel; oat futures were unchanged to 1 cent higher with December at $ 1.40 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were 1 -RCB- cents to 5 -LCB- cents higher with November at $ 5.78 a bushel. Livestock futures were mostly higher while pork-belly futures were mostly lower in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> after bellies soared the 2-cents-a-pound daily limit on Wednesday. Live cattle futures were .05 cent to .40 cent higher with October at 71.55 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .40 cent higher with September at 83.30 cents a pound; hogs were .45 cent lower to .35 cent higher with October at 42.12 cents a pound; frozies were .75 cent lower to 1.40 cents higher with February at 49 cents a pound. Cattle futures retreated Wednesday while pork futures advanced.
</TEXT>
