<HEAD>Mobil Ordered To Pay $21 Million in Contract Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal jury has awarded <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> more than $ 21 million for an alleged breach of contract by <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to buy pure phosphorus produced at plants in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> contended <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> violated a five-year agreement to buy the phosphorus and other products, including detergents and lubrication additives, at <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> plants in suburban <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>. A six-member jury in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> deliberated two hours Wednesday before awarding $ 21,126,557 to <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> contended during the trial, which began Sept. 11, that its sale of the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> plants to <PERSON> Albright </PERSON> & amp; <ORGANIZATION> Wilson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in April 1985 negated the contract with <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION>. `` We obviously disagree with the verdict. It's a complex commercial case,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahrens </PERSON>, a lawyer for <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION>. He said <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> would ask the judge to overturn the verdict or order a new trial. <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> produced elemental phosphorus _ the pure, uncombined chemical element _ at plants in <LOCATION> Soda </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn </LOCATION>.
