<FIRST>u f AM-OPEC Bjt   09-21 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OPEC, Bjt,0758</SECOND>
<HEAD>OPEC Ministers Will Hold Meeting on Contentious Quota Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> ministers will meet this weekend to tackle the troublesome issue of how to fairly divvy up oil-production shares among the 13 nations. Some want much more than their current allotment. But analysts were skeptical the eight-member committee of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> would do much more than review proposals for reworking output quotas assigned each member. <PERSON> Fergus </PERSON> <PERSON> MacLeod </PERSON>, analyst at the investment firm of <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoete </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wedd </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, said he expected `` not very much'' to come out of the meeting that begins Saturday in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. Failure to reach any meaningful conclusion on current production, however, could be `` very dangerous'' because countries might widen their oil taps and increase their already high production level, he said. Another analyst, <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Antill </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> NatWest </ORGANIZATION>, predicted the ministers would `` leave the fighting until November'' when all 13 ministers are scheduled to gather for a key year-end meeting in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. `` They will discuss -LRB- quotas -RRB- but they will take no decision,'' said <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Terzian </PERSON>, editor of the oil publication Petrostrategies in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. The ministers are at odds over how the cartel divides up and sets the ceilings for each country's crude output. Some countries, like <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION>, want a larger share of the production pie. Both have been ignoring their quotas in recent months and pumping at higher levels. Moreover, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> just opened the second phase of a twin pipeline across <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, which will add more than a million barrels a day to its export capacity. The move increases the likelihood it will want a higher quota. Analysts estimate <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s current production at close to 22 million barrels a day, well over the cap of 19.5 million set in June for the last six months of the year. Prices have been lower than earlier in the year. A basket of seven crudes monitored by <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> was priced at $ 17.04 a barrel last week, under the cartel's target of $ 18. West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil, has been trading in the range of $ 19.50 to $ 20 for a 42-gallon barrel. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude normally sells for about $ 2 above the OPEC-monitored crudes. Indonesian Oil Minister <PERSON> Ginandjar </PERSON> <PERSON> Kartasasmita </PERSON> was quoted earlier this month as saying he was not satisfied with the market's recent performance. `` We have not been able to reach the $ 18 per barrel price level that we wanted, except for a few weeks earlier this summer,'' he told <ORGANIZATION> OPECNA </ORGANIZATION>, the cartel's news agency. At their June conference, the ministers agreed to begin the tough task of finding a more acceptable way to figure out each country's take of the cartel's daily output But analysts detected less willingness now _ with higher production and weaker prices _ to try to solve the problem. Nevertheless, they expected <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> to put forth proposals for drawing up quotas that would consider only oil-related factors. Some members have suggested that quotas take into account a country's `` need'' for oil revenue as determined by its foreign debt, balance of payments and population. While quotas were likely to grab most of the attention, the ministers were also expected to decide whether to boost their supply cap to 20 million barrels a day in the last quarter. An <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> official, who demanded anonymity, said there was `` a slight possibility'' they would do so. `` They may want to narrow the gap between the quota and actual production,'' said <PERSON> Bahman </PERSON> <PERSON> Karbassioun </PERSON>, an oil consultant in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. But he said production `` could go even higher'' if countries failed to agree to abide by their ceilings. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported in its Monthly Oil Market Report that the nations lifted output in August to 21.6 million barrels a day, the highest so far this year. The agency is an arm of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, made up of two-dozen Western nations. The eight-member Long-term Strategy and Price-Monitoring Committee includes ministers from <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. The other five nations _ <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> _ were also invited to attend. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s oil chief, <PERSON> Hisham </PERSON> <PERSON> Nazer </PERSON>, was reported recovering from surgery earlier this month in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and was not expected to attend.
</TEXT>
