<HEAD>Grain Futures Rally, Bracing for Freeze</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures prices rallied strongly Thursday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> as the markets braced for the first hard freeze of the season in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. On other markets, silver futures were sharply higher for the second consecutive session; energy futures were mixed; and livestock and meat futures were mixed. Wheat futures settled 2 cents to 3 cents higher with the contract for delivery in December at $ 3.94 -RCB- a bushel; corn futures were unchanged to 3 cents higher with December at $ 2.31 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 1 -LCB- cents to 2 cents higher with December at $ 1.41 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents lower to 7 \ cents higher with November at $ 5.82 -RCB- a bushel The rally was rooted in forecasts for freezing temperatures this weekend and early next week, possibly reaching as far south as northern <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. `` This is record-breaking or near-record-breaking type cold coming in,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Notis </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Freese-Notis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a private forecasting firm in <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. Most corn and soybean crops west of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> have matured beyond the danger stage. But the crops in other Midwestern states east of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> _ especially soybeans _ are susceptible to freeze damage. <PERSON> Notis </PERSON> estimated that 500 million bushels of soybeans, a little less than a quarter of the crop, were still vulnerable to frost damage and that 45 million to 70 million bushels could be hurt by the arctic high pressure system sweeping down from northwestern <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Most of that damage is likely to occur in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, he said. In the western Corn Belt, where the crops are more mature, `` I do n't think you're talking about yield losses, I think you're talking about quality problems,'' said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustafson </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION> Frost could slow the natural drying of mature corn and lock some chlorophyll into not-quite-ripe soybeans, causing some discoloration, <PERSON> Gustafson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Michelsen </PERSON>, a meteorologist with <ORGANIZATION> Murray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Trettl </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Northfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, predicted a less-severe freeze than <PERSON> Notis </PERSON>. Still, he said, `` I would expect to see a killing frost over a great portion of the upper <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> by early next week. We've got quite a cold snap here.'' Silver futures scooted up sharply on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as the dollar weakened but gold futures made only slight gains, held back by the oil market's lackluster showing. Gold settled 10 cents to 60 cents higher with October at $ 366.30 a troy ounce; silver was 6 cents to 6.4 cents higher with September at $ 5.181 a troy ounce. Crude-oil futures were narrowly mixed on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> but near-month gasoline and heating-oil futures rose sharply amid concerns about potential damage to refineries from Hurricane Hugo. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 6 cents lower to 3 cents higher with November at $ 19.62 a barrel; heating oil was .25 cent to 1.03 cents higher with October at 57.58 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .30 cent lower to 2.12 cents higher with October at 61.86 cents a gallon. Livestock and meat futures finished mixed on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .55 cent higher with October at 71.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .20 cent higher with September at 83.10 cents a pound; hogs were .43 cent lower to .13 cent higher with October at 41.90 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.10 cents lower to .60 cent higher with February at 48.75 cents a pound.
