<HEAD>Immunex Transforming Into Pharmaceutical Company</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 4th graf pvs, `Overall, I... to UPDATE with
closing stock price; PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `Immunex uses...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Immunex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday announced a plan that will transform it from a research-dominated firm in medical biotechnology into a conventional pharmaceutical company. The 8-year-old company, based in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, said it would achieve the transition primarily by reacquiring rights to sell Immunex-developed products in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In return, its business partners will get rights to some other <ORGANIZATION> Immunex </ORGANIZATION> products, primarily for overseas distribution. <ORGANIZATION> Immunex </ORGANIZATION>'s plan will require the company to build a sales staff from scratch, but it should permit it to keep more of the profits from its work, said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Labe </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Simpson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` Overall, I think it's an aggressive strategy,'' <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON> said. In over-the-counter trading Thursday, <ORGANIZATION> Immunex </ORGANIZATION> stock fell 50 cents to $ 16.50. <ORGANIZATION> Immunex </ORGANIZATION> uses gene-splicing and other biotechnology techniques to create products for medical treatment, mainly products that either promote or inhibit the activity of the immune system. Products that are being tested on people in government-supervised trials include ones for cancer therapy, wound healing and protection of bone marrow from the harmful effects of radiation therapy and chemotherapy. The biggest threat to <ORGANIZATION> Immunex </ORGANIZATION> is that other companies developing products in the same field could challenge its patent position, <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON> said. At the end of 1988 <ORGANIZATION> Immunex </ORGANIZATION> had marketing rights for only two of its own products. After the changes announced Thursday, some of which occurred earlier this year, it will have rights to more than a dozen. Like many small biotech companies, <ORGANIZATION> Immunex </ORGANIZATION> had given marketing rights for its products to other companies in exchange for research funding and help in manufacturing. Even after the deals, other companies will retain foreign marketing rights for many Immunex-related products. <ORGANIZATION> Immunex </ORGANIZATION>'s partners include <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Behringwerke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Syntex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION> The restructuring will give <ORGANIZATION> Immunex </ORGANIZATION> a five-year head start on its plan to transform itself into a conventional pharmaceutical company by 1995, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Duzan </PERSON>, the chairman and chief executive, said at a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> news conference. `` We're going to be a modest-sized but fully integrated pharmaceutical company,'' <PERSON> Duzan </PERSON> said in an interview. <ORGANIZATION> Immunex </ORGANIZATION> said it is poised to enter the cancer market in the coming five years and the infectious disease and autoimmune disease markets in 1995 to 2000. Autoimmune diseases are those such as arthritis and diabetes in which the body is attacked by its own immune-system defenses. <ORGANIZATION> Immunex </ORGANIZATION> reacquired worldwide marketing and manufacturing rights to interleukin-1 receptor and interleukin-4 receptor products by restructuring its joint venture with <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Sterling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. It also reacquired <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> co-marketing and manufacturing rights from <ORGANIZATION> Behringwerke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> for CM-CSF -LRB- granulocyte macrophage colony stimulating factor -RRB-, interleukin-3 and other CSF products. In return, it gave <ORGANIZATION> Behringwerke </ORGANIZATION> the foreign rights to a package of receptor products, including receptors for interleukin-1, interleukin-4 and other undisclosed receptor products. It retained all North American rights for all receptor products. Receptors can block the destructive action of the immune system by serving as decoys for attackers.
</TEXT>
