<FIRST>r f AM-FraudSettlement     09-21 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fraud Settlement,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>ITT Consumer Financial To Repay Millions in Consumer Fraud Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> ITT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> agreed Thursday to pay what could total more than $ 50 million for allegedly bilking hundreds of thousands of Californians with loans later packed with extra requirements. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> called the civil settlement capping a three-year investigation `` one of the largest and most sweeping consumer fraud settlements in American history.'' He said Minneapolis-based <ORGANIZATION> ITT </ORGANIZATION> lured applicants into expensive loans packed with extras such as various forms of insurance and thrift club memberships. Applicants were bilked of as much as $ 2,000 each, he said. <ORGANIZATION> ITT </ORGANIZATION> is the parent company of co-defendants <ORGANIZATION> Aetna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> _ which <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> said had no connection with <ORGANIZATION> Aetna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> _ <ORGANIZATION> ITT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lyndon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Property </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> ITT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lyndon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. All the consumers involved are to be sent letters explaining the settlement <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> estimated as many as 300,000 victims but said only about one third are expected to seek restitution, with the total return between $ 25 million and $ 50 million. <ORGANIZATION> ITT </ORGANIZATION> also will pay $ 10.5 million to establish consumer protection trust funds, $ 8.67 million in civil penalties and $ 575,000 for legal costs and a toll-free phone number for consumers claiming refunds. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> ITT </ORGANIZATION> took advantage of people `` in desperate need of money'' and charged up to 35 percent interest on loans and attached items. <ORGANIZATION> ITT </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement it agreed to restitution at the same time a civil suit was filed Thursday in <ORGANIZATION> Alameda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. It neither admitted nort denied wrongdoing. <ORGANIZATION> ITT </ORGANIZATION> said the accusations `` without doubt were contraventions to our procedures and not a pattern of behavior condoned by the company,'' but added that `` pre-existing safeguards'' existed on loans and insurance. Claimants will be entitled to interest paid, interest on the interest for years involved and the cost of all extras.
</TEXT>
