<SECOND>AM-Morgan-Loan Reserve, 1st Ld-Writethru,0781</SECOND>
<HEAD>J.P. Morgan Adding $2 Billion to Loan-Loss Reserve</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with background, analyst comments; adds
byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> moved ahead of other major banking companies Thursday by adding $ 2 billion to its cushion of reserves for loan losses, indicating deeper pessimism about the chances of repayment by developing countries <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>'s action was far more severe than those taken earlier this week by <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>'s reserves now equal 100 percent of its medium - and long-term loans to developing In contrast, <PERSON> Chase </PERSON>'s equal 46 percent after its addition this week and Manufacturers Hanover's 36 percent <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, the parent of <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said it would continue doing business in developing countries but would focus on merchant banking rather than general lending. Merchant banking involves providing advice, trading and investing and finance. `` We will continue to consider lending in appropriate specific transactions. We intend to continue to play a constructive role in developing countries,'' <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Baum </PERSON> said. The bigger cushion indicates <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> has gotten tired of prolonged and unfruitful negotiations with debtor nations on repayment, said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Berman </PERSON>, a banking analyst at <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION>. `` I think they just want to say the hell with this,'' he said. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, the nation's third-largest bank-holding company, also is one of the financially strongest. That means it was able to take the punishment of the $ 2 billion addition, which will result in a loss of about $ 1.8 billion in the current quarter. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>'s action could be an indication of trouble for the negotiations on debt relief under a plan devised by <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, <PERSON> Berman </PERSON> said. Less developed countries have debts of $ 1.3 trillion. `` Early on in this process everybody sort of pulled together, followed the lead of <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Berman </PERSON> said. `` Everybody is sort of cutting and running now and pursuing their own interest.'' This week's round of additions to loan-loss reserves was triggered by the conclusion last week of an accord to provide debt relief to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> under the <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> plan, which emphasizes debt forgiveness by the banks. The terms of the <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> accord made banks acknowledge that they had been overly optimistic in their earlier expectations for repayment. But <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>'s action seemed to go beyond necessity, <PERSON> Berman </PERSON> said. `` Economic and political problems have intensified in several countries where we have significant exposure, including problems in paying interest when due,'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Preston </PERSON>, <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>'s chairman, said in a written statement. <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> said he was concerned that debtor countries could be expecting more help from the <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> plan than the industrial countries are likely to provide. He also said: `` Achieving satisfactory loan restructuring agreements will also be more and more difficult because of increasingly divergent approaches to LDC -LRB- less-developed country -RRB- debt problem among bank lenders and among governments.'' <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> now has a total of $ 3 billion in loan-loss reserves, with $ 2.8 billion of that unofficially allocated to loans to developing countries. That $ 2.8 billion is equal to 70 percent of <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>'s total loans to developing countries, and 100 percent of the medium-and long-term loans to those nations In an indication of <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>'s financial strength, <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and Standards and Poor's both confirmed their investment-grade ratings on Morgan senior debt. The last big round of additions to reserves was in late 1987, and many banking companies have not taken any action since then. For example, <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s loan-loss reserves equal just 28 percent of its loans to developing countries, the level it reached in late 1987, spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Salmans </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it would take a $ 1.31 billion charge in the third quarter, largely to boost its reserves for troubled loans to developing countries. <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> also announced plans to raise $ 500 million by selling new common shares. <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> said its reserve increase would boost its reserves for losses on loans to developing countries to 46 percent of its $ 6.2 billion in such loans and would produce a third-quarter loss for the holding company of $ 1.11 billion. Manufacturers Hanover on Monday added $ 950 million to its loan-loss reserves and sold control of its asset-based lending unit, <ORGANIZATION> CIT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Dai-Ichi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kangyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> for $ 1.28 billion. Manufacturers Hanover also agreed to sell a 4.9 percent stake in the parent company to <ORGANIZATION> Dai-Ichi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kangyo </ORGANIZATION> for another $ 120 million. Manufacturers Hanover said the addition to its loan-loss reserve would produce a third-quarter loss of $ 775 million.
</TEXT>
