<FIRST>r f AM-IMF-WorldBankDebt     09-21 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IMF-World Bank Debt,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Bank Reports Incomes Up in Asia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Incomes rose sharply for people in key <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> countries last year, with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s increase almost twice that of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday. In <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the average went up to $ 12,480 from 1987's $ 11,780, while average income in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> rose to $ 14,080 from $ 13,650. The figures are corrected for inflation. The data show that compared with wealthier countries, the Third World is losing its share of the world's income, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, who heads the bank's office on social and economic data. `` Comparatively, the poor are getting poorer,'' he said. People in countries where earnings are lower showed more modest gains. The average South Korean had a proportionately large increase: from $ 2,760 to $ 3,060 in 1988. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> was up from $ 310 to $ 330, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> from $ 620 to $ 680 and <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> showed a sharp rise from $ 830 to $ 940. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s figure for 1988 was not in yet. In 1987, the average Chinese had an income of $ 510. No figure was given for <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, which is not a member of the bank. `` For 1989, we expect to see a modest correction in what have been very high rates of growth down to more sustainable levels for <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and several middle-income countries,'' said <PERSON> Attila </PERSON> <PERSON> Karaosmanoglu </PERSON>, the bank's vice-president for <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>'s figures deal largely with <ORGANIZATION> Third </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> countries, since it is the largest source of loans to raise their standards of living. Statistics for 1988 are not yet complete, officials said. Scattered reports for a few European countries that borrow from the bank showed increases in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> from $ 4,810 to $ 5,010 and <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> from $ 4,310 to $ 4,440. But in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> there was a drop, to $ 3,080 from $ 3,180 in 1987. In <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the 1988 figure fell to $ 1,800 from $ 1,830. The significant losses came in the larger countries. In <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, which accounts for a third of the production in the continent, average income dropped to $ 1,930 from $ 1,980. In <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> the fall was to $ 2,260 from $ 2,300 and in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> from $ 3,390 to $ 3,290. <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> rose to $ 2,370 from $ 2,280, while <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s figure was not available. For southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the bank's figures show a steady decline since 1980, when the average income for the area was $ 570 a year. In 1988 it was $ 440. The Republic of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is not included in this calculation.
</TEXT>
