<HEAD>Bail Denied in Du Pont Extortion Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> magistrate denied bail Thursday to one of three defendants charged with trying to extort $ 10 million from <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in exchange for trade secrets stolen from the chemical giant. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Magistrate <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> denied bail for <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> <PERSON> Skerianz </PERSON> during a pretrial detention hearing, saying there was a possibility <PERSON> Skerianz </PERSON> would not show for trial because he was an international traveler with `` considerable resources.'' <PERSON> Skerianz </PERSON> was returned to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> last week. He had fought extradition since his arrest there earlier this year. Defense attorney <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Zappa </PERSON> had sought limited electronic monitoring for Skerianz. Skerianz and two other suspects have been in custody at undisclosed locations since their arrests in February. All are charged with one count each of attempted extortion. They face up to 20 years in prison and a $ 250,000 fine each. The federal government plans to drop charges against a fourth suspect, <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Bianchini </PERSON>, who is living in a private home in <LOCATION> Elsmere </LOCATION>. According to court documents, the charges will be dropped in exchange for her testimony if needed. The three Argentinian nationals and <PERSON> Skerianz </PERSON> were arrested in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, after an aborted meeting at which <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> was to pay $ 10 million to the suspects in exchange for `` sensitive documents'' concerning Lycra, <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON>'s trade name for spandex fiber, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said. The suspects had all worked at <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON>'s plant in Mercedes, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, one of several plants that make the fiber. Spandex is used primarily in swimming suits, leotards and pantyhose.
