<SECOND>BC-China-Soviet Trade,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>China-Soviet Barter Trade Gains Favor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> prefers to sell its goods for Western hard currency but its imports from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, paid for by bartering, are way up, the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reports. `` Chinese imports of goods such as timber and fertilizer, where the quality of the Soviet commodity is comparable to that elsewhere, will probably grow this year as <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> turns to barter to conserve foreign exchange,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> said in an analysis prepared for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and released this week to the press. Sino-Soviet trade grew 27 percent least year to a two-way total of $ 3.3 billion and figures for the first half of 1989 show even stronger growth, with Chinese imports surging by 63 percent and exports up 12 percent, the report said. Trade along the Soviet-Chinese border has risen swiftly to account for 10 percent of the two countries' trade, welcomed by remote Chinese provinces lacking easy access to other markets, it noted. The report also disclosed that 8,000 Chinese laborers are working on projects in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> under arrangements generally providing payment to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> with a percentage of the production. At least 5,000 more are expected to follow, it said. The two countries normalized relations last spring, providing a boost to their economic relations which, however, appear to be reaching their limits, since <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> will continue to favor Western technology, said the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
