<FIRST>u f AM-FantasyTakeover     09-21 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fantasy Takeover,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carl Icahn, Jesse Jackson, Others Play Simulated Takeover Game</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Do takeover battles really end when the power system blows during a climactic board meeting? Probably not. But that was about the only thing clearly out of character Thursday as <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> chairman and investor <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> and a cast of corporate and civic heavyweights including the Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> put some of their well-honed moves on public display in a three-hour simulated takeover. `` I think it's been incredibly realistic,'' <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, the dean of the <ORGANIZATION> Graduate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Fordham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said shortly before the lights dimmed and the microphones went dead. He said the participants in the program that people from his school designed were `` acting as they do at real board meetings.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, the former head of the <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Richfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> who played the role of the chief executive of the company under siege, rated the interplay among the board members `` surprisingly good.'' But <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>, the chief executive of the investment banking firm <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, cautioned that there were limits to the imagined reality. `` What we are doing in 10 minutes takes 10 days,'' he said. In the game, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> played an investment banker advising <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, who was cast as an investor with a small stake in the beleaguered target company and was considering launching an alternative takeover bid. The program was put on at a conference run by the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, an international organization of management groups. The simulation went a step further than recent exercises in which prominent people in various fields are brought together for a moderator-led discussion about a hypothetical case. In this corporate war game, the directors of the imaginary <ORGANIZATION> Main </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a Southern retailing company, met in one room to mourn the death of their chairman and to assess their options should the swirl of takeover rumors produce an offer. At the same time, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> was closeted in a room across the hall, talking one-by-one with with financial advisers, union officials and representatives of a foundation that had an 18 percent stake in the company about his plans to make a bid for the company. Several hundred people attending the conference were invited to walk back and forth between the rooms as they wished as the scenario unfolded through a series of twists and turns. Conference staffers added to the atmosphere with periodic updates on the company's stock price and news headlines, such as <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s notice that he bought an 8 percent stake in the firm Observers got to watch <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> court the unions and the foundation for support before going to the board. They saw him needle his investment bankers about the fees they wanted to finance the bid and get so swept up in the franctic pace of activity that he chided an inattentive assistant by blurting out, `` Come on, you're not at <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>.'' When <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> finally got in to see the board, he found they had been doing their homework as well and felt that neither his offer nor a competing bid was worth accepting. Board members said they would investigate a recapitalization instead. The real-life power outage cut short any additional countermoves, and the game was declared finished. `` I enjoyed it,'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> concurred, saying `` It was entertaining. It was fun.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, the civil rights activist who played a foundation representative interested in protecting the communities and workers served by the stores, said the game created a `` healthy environment'' for discussion of tough issues. `` I hope it increases all of our sensitivity,'' he said.
</TEXT>
